H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"PO4H3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"phosphoric acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C7H14N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-[(2-amino-3-methylbutanoyl)amino]acetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valylglycine-like dipeptide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"aminoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-mediated two-electron reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-S minerals gives adsorbed formyl equivalents and releases formate into vent fluids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step follows the iron-sulfur world and alkaline vent framework in which greigite/mackinawite analogs of biological Fe-S clusters catalyze CO2 reduction to formate under H2-rich vent conditions (Russell et al., 1994; Martin and Russell, 2007). The thermodynamic favorability of amino-acid-relevant carbon fixation in hot reduced hydrothermal systems is consistent with Amend and Shock (1998).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Magnetite-mediated hydrothermal carbon fixation to acetate and pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor/alkaline vent interface, reducing, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential mineral-catalyzed CO2 hydrogenation and C-C bond formation generate acetate and pyruvate as reduced carboxylates in a vent-like proto-metabolic network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The network uses the user-required hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis and Fischer-Tropsch-like Fe-oxide chemistry as a literature-grounded proxy for hydrothermal production of central keto acids. This is consistent with vent carbon-fixation logic and reductive protometabolic chemistry discussed for hydrothermal systems (Amend and Shock, 1998; Martin and Russell, 2007; Muchowska, Varma, and Moran, 2019). The exact direct abiotic pyruvate-to-valine branch remains incompletely demonstrated, so this node is a necessary network connector grounded in reported hydrothermal keto-acid chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/FeS2 mineral system\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline to near-neutral, anoxic, H2/H2S-bearing\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia is followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine on Fe-sulfur/iron mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on freshly precipitated FeS/Fe(OH)2 and related iron-bearing minerals is experimentally supported, and pyruvate-to-alanine is directly demonstrated in several systems (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber and Wachtershauser, 2003; Barge et al., 2019; Kaur et al., 2024). This reaction anchors the hydrothermal side of the network and motivates extension to alpha-ketoisovalerate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical generation of HCN and formaldehyde from reducing atmospheric feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalytic mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, reducing atmosphere/ocean-atmosphere interface, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical and discharge-like atmospheric processing produces nitriles and small carbonyls that dissolve into surface waters; TiO2 enhances photoredox transformations and product persistence.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Miller-Urey-type atmospheric energy sources generate HCN and aldehydes that subsequently undergo Strecker chemistry, with valine appearing in archived spark discharge products upon reanalysis (Miller, 1953; Ring et al., 1972; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011). TiO2 is included because semiconductor photocatalysis is relevant to prebiotic surface photochemistry and carbonyl/nucleobase precursor production (Saladino et al., 2006).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized formose/aldol conversion of formaldehyde to acetaldehyde-rich carbonyl mixtures\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate mineral stabilization of reactive carbonyl pools\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pools, basic episodes, wet-dry cycling, UV-exposed\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde undergoes base-promoted carbonyl homologation and disproportionation within borate-stabilized mixtures, furnishing small aldehydes including acetaldehyde as a network-accessible C2 hub.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formose-type and related surface carbonyl chemistry are established sources of mixed aldehydes, although not selectively of valine precursors. The literature specifically notes that formose chemistry generates complex aldehyde mixtures and may contribute trace higher aldehydes while not cleanly yielding branched precursors (Patel et al., 2015; Preiner et al., 2023; the review findings explicitly describe formose chemistry as a nonselective contributor rather than a direct valine route). This reaction is included as a literature-consistent feeder to acetaldehyde, not as a claimed selective source of isobutyraldehyde.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"NiS-like sulfide mineral aldol diversification from acetaldehyde to trace branched aldehydes including isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"transition-metal sulfide mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic or geothermal pools, concentrating episodes, low selectivity, branched products are minor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-bound acetaldehyde undergoes enolization, aldol diversification, fragmentation, and rearrangement within complex aldehyde networks to furnish low-yield branched C4 aldehydes including isobutyraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report identifies branched aldehyde generation as the central bottleneck and specifically points to aldol diversification on NiS catalysts as one of the most promising routes, while emphasizing poor selectivity for isobutyraldehyde (Preiner et al., 2023). This reaction is therefore explicitly low-flux and bottleneck-limited, matching the literature rather than overstating plausibility.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark/discharge-radical route to isobutyraldehyde in atmospheric product mixtures\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral capture/concentration after atmospheric discharge chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"lightning/spark discharge or volcanic electrical activity; reducing gas mixtures; dissolution into surface waters\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Atmospheric radical recombination produces complex aldehyde mixtures including rare branched aldehydes; mineral-bearing surface pools capture the products together with HCN for downstream Strecker chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Valine in Miller-Urey-type experiments is explained by radical chemistry generating branched aldehydes among complex product mixtures; improved analyses confirmed valine in archived discharge samples (Keefe, Newton, and Miller, 1995; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011). This step follows the report's conclusion that spark discharge is one of the few experimentally supported contexts where the valine precursor plausibly appears.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical Strecker formation of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273-323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces in aqueous solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH ~9, free NH3 available, mild temperatures, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Isobutyraldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine/Schiff base, followed by cyanide addition to produce 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the best-established prebiotic route to valine and uses the exact key precursor identified in the literature. The mechanism and pH dependence are directly supported by Strecker analyses and computational free-energy studies (Miller and Van Trump, 1981; Keefe, Newton, and Miller, 1995; Devergne et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis through amide intermediate; irreversible product-forming step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis through an amide intermediate irreversibly yields racemic valine, pulling the Strecker equilibrium forward.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of the aminonitrile is the irreversible driving step in Strecker valine formation and is well established experimentally and theoretically (Miller and Van Trump, 1981; Devergne et al., 2021). Aminonitrile persistence and hydrolysis timescales are also discussed by Miller (1998).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs-type bridge from isobutyraldehyde to alpha-ketoisovalerate/valine manifold\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration in aqueous pool chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"CO2-present, cyanide/ammonia-rich solution; hydantoin-accessible chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde-derived cyanide/ammonia chemistry under CO2-rich conditions accesses hydantoin-related intermediates that bridge Strecker chemistry and alpha-keto-acid/alpha-amino-acid manifolds.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti et al. (2022) showed that Bucherer-Bergs chemistry provides a bridge between aldehyde-based Strecker reactions and alpha-keto acid metabolism through hydantoin intermediates. This node is included to connect the validated aldehyde route to the keto-acid branch without inventing an unrelated pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Protometabolic condensation from pyruvate to alpha-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated prebiotic pools or mineral interfaces; metabolically congruent but experimentally unresolved for selective prebiotic flux\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Non-enzymatic carbon-carbon bond formation within protometabolic keto-acid chemistry yields the branched alpha-keto acid alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate-centered carbonyl networks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies alpha-ketoisovalerate as a metabolically congruent alternative precursor whose prebiotic formation could arise from pyruvate-centered condensation chemistry analogous to modern acetolactate logic, or broader non-enzymatic Krebs-like chemistry, but notes that direct experimental demonstration remains incomplete. This reaction is therefore explicitly speculative but literature-motivated and necessary to connect the reductive amination branch (Muchowska, Varma, and Moran, 2019; Copley, Smith, and Morowitz, 2005; the review findings).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Mineral-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/pyrite or related iron-bearing reductive mineral system\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH ~8-11, anoxic, H2-bearing vent or vent-derived interface; extension of demonstrated keto-acid reductive amination chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-ketoisovalerate forms an imine with ammonia and is reduced on iron-bearing mineral surfaces to valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is experimentally demonstrated on FeS/H2S, Fe(OH)2-derived systems, mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides, pyrite-related minerals, and metallic Ni; extension to alpha-ketoisovalerate is explicitly supported in principle by the literature although not always tested as the exact substrate (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber and Wachtershauser, 2003; Barge et al., 2019; Kaur et al., 2024; Nature Communications, 2024 pyrite photocatalysis). This is a literature-supported alternative entry to valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic surface chemistry feeding shared HCN and small aldehyde pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanide-sulfide-phosphate photoredox network on mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, H2S/Cu photoredox style chemistry, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-centered photoredox chemistry in the presence of sulfide and phosphate yields reactive C1-C2 carbonyl and amidine/imine intermediates that reinforce Strecker-accessible feedstock pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated unified cyanosulfidic chemistry generating nucleotide, lipid, and amino-acid precursor pools from HCN, H2S, UV, and phosphate. The review emphasizes that published schemes mainly build C1-C3 products and do not directly furnish valine's branched precursor; accordingly this reaction only feeds the shared HCN/small-aldehyde pool rather than claiming direct valine synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminonitrile preservation by formamide/formylating pool chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"formamide-rich transient drying pools; protection against Strecker reversal\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide-enabled N-formylation/protection chemistry stabilizes aminonitrile pools against reversal, increasing persistence until hydrolysis to amino acid occurs.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, 2023) showed that N-formylation of aminonitriles in formamide solvent can protect aminonitriles from reversion of Strecker equilibrium. This does not create a new molecule node here, but it provides a literature-based persistence pathway that supports downstream valine formation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Wet-dry clay-assisted peptide capture of valine into short peptides\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373-393K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling in mineral-rich surface pools; concentration-driven condensation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Repeated drying and rehydration drives ester-amide exchange and peptide bond formation, trapping valine into small peptides that stabilize localized product pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Wet-dry cycling is a well-supported downstream fate for amino acids in prebiotic pools and is especially relevant for converting low concentrations into retained oligomers (Forsythe et al., 2015; Campbell et al., 2019). This reaction places valine in the broader biochemical/prebiotic network rather than as an isolated endpoint.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical Strecker from atmospheric isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Spark/discharge chemistry generates HCN and rare isobutyraldehyde; surface Strecker chemistry gives valine aminonitrile, followed by hydrolysis to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol-diversification Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface small-carbonyl chemistry generates acetaldehyde from formaldehyde, then low-yield branched aldehyde formation feeds the Strecker route to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface Strecker route via pyruvate-centered carbon fixation\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation produces pyruvate and reduced carbon that feed surface carbonyl pools, eventually yielding isobutyraldehyde and valine by Strecker chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic-assisted Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN-rich cyanosulfidic surface chemistry reinforces formaldehyde and acetaldehyde supply, increasing flux into the branched aldehyde bottleneck and then through Strecker chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs bridge to valine from isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde enters a CO2-assisted Bucherer-Bergs/Strecker manifold that bridges aldehyde chemistry and keto-acid chemistry before yielding valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination from alpha-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoisovalerate formed in protometabolic chemistry undergoes mineral-catalyzed reductive amination at alkaline vent interfaces to produce valine directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Vent-to-protometabolic keto-acid route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation gives pyruvate, which enters protometabolic condensation to alpha-ketoisovalerate and then reductive amination to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Atmospheric aldehyde plus keto-acid convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde from surface photochemistry converges with hydrothermal pyruvate to form alpha-ketoisovalerate, followed by reductive amination to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminonitrile preservation-enhanced Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Classical Strecker synthesis is followed by formamide-mediated aminonitrile stabilization, increasing the chance of eventual hydrolysis to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Integrated hydrothermal-surface-biochemical route to retained valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation and surface Strecker chemistry produce valine, which is then captured in downstream peptide-forming pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_016\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "This network models prebiotic valine synthesis as a connected bipartite graph centered on two literature-supported entry points: (i) the experimentally validated Strecker route from isobutyraldehyde, ammonia, and HCN through the aminonitrile intermediate to racemic valine, and (ii) reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate on iron-bearing minerals. The design explicitly treats isobutyraldehyde and alpha-ketoisovalerate as bottleneck branched intermediates, consistent with the literature. Hydrothermal reactions generate reduced C1-C3 feedstocks and pyruvate under alkaline vent conditions on Fe-S and Fe-oxide minerals; surface reactions use UV, wet-dry cycles, cyanosulfidic chemistry, borate-stabilized carbonyl chemistry, and spark/photochemical atmospheric inputs to furnish HCN, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and trace branched aldehydes; biochemical/prebiotic reactions assemble valine from shared intermediates and include transamination and peptide-forming downstream capture. Ten pathways are represented as overlapping routes through the same connected network, with major convergence at HCN, acetaldehyde, isobutyraldehyde, alpha-ketoisovalerate, and the valine aminonitrile.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2CO", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H3O2-", "iupac_name": "ethanoate", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H3O3-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-4(2)3-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H7O3-", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoate", "common_name": "alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "valine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(6)3-7/h4-5H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "CH2N2O", "iupac_name": "methanimidamide", "common_name": "formamidine", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H9NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-2-methylpropanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-aminoisobutyric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO2/c1-4(2,5)3(6)7/h5H2,1-2H3,(H,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "PO4H3", "iupac_name": "phosphoric acid", "common_name": "phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C7H14N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-[(2-amino-3-methylbutanoyl)amino]acetic acid", "common_name": "valylglycine-like dipeptide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Surface-mediated two-electron reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-S minerals gives adsorbed formyl equivalents and releases formate into vent fluids.", "reasoning": "This step follows the iron-sulfur world and alkaline vent framework in which greigite/mackinawite analogs of biological Fe-S clusters catalyze CO2 reduction to formate under H2-rich vent conditions (Russell et al., 1994; Martin and Russell, 2007). The thermodynamic favorability of amino-acid-relevant carbon fixation in hot reduced hydrothermal systems is consistent with Amend and Shock (1998)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Magnetite-mediated hydrothermal carbon fixation to acetate and pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor/alkaline vent interface, reducing, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Sequential mineral-catalyzed CO2 hydrogenation and C-C bond formation generate acetate and pyruvate as reduced carboxylates in a vent-like proto-metabolic network.", "reasoning": "The network uses the user-required hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis and Fischer-Tropsch-like Fe-oxide chemistry as a literature-grounded proxy for hydrothermal production of central keto acids. This is consistent with vent carbon-fixation logic and reductive protometabolic chemistry discussed for hydrothermal systems (Amend and Shock, 1998; Martin and Russell, 2007; Muchowska, Varma, and Moran, 2019). The exact direct abiotic pyruvate-to-valine branch remains incompletely demonstrated, so this node is a necessary network connector grounded in reported hydrothermal keto-acid chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-373K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "FeS/FeS2 mineral system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline to near-neutral, anoxic, H2/H2S-bearing"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia is followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine on Fe-sulfur/iron mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on freshly precipitated FeS/Fe(OH)2 and related iron-bearing minerals is experimentally supported, and pyruvate-to-alanine is directly demonstrated in several systems (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber and Wachtershauser, 2003; Barge et al., 2019; Kaur et al., 2024). This reaction anchors the hydrothermal side of the network and motivates extension to alpha-ketoisovalerate."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface photochemical generation of HCN and formaldehyde from reducing atmospheric feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalytic mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, reducing atmosphere/ocean-atmosphere interface, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical and discharge-like atmospheric processing produces nitriles and small carbonyls that dissolve into surface waters; TiO2 enhances photoredox transformations and product persistence.", "reasoning": "Miller-Urey-type atmospheric energy sources generate HCN and aldehydes that subsequently undergo Strecker chemistry, with valine appearing in archived spark discharge products upon reanalysis (Miller, 1953; Ring et al., 1972; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011). TiO2 is included because semiconductor photocatalysis is relevant to prebiotic surface photochemistry and carbonyl/nucleobase precursor production (Saladino et al., 2006)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Borate-stabilized formose/aldol conversion of formaldehyde to acetaldehyde-rich carbonyl mixtures", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate mineral stabilization of reactive carbonyl pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pools, basic episodes, wet-dry cycling, UV-exposed"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde undergoes base-promoted carbonyl homologation and disproportionation within borate-stabilized mixtures, furnishing small aldehydes including acetaldehyde as a network-accessible C2 hub.", "reasoning": "Formose-type and related surface carbonyl chemistry are established sources of mixed aldehydes, although not selectively of valine precursors. The literature specifically notes that formose chemistry generates complex aldehyde mixtures and may contribute trace higher aldehydes while not cleanly yielding branched precursors (Patel et al., 2015; Preiner et al., 2023; the review findings explicitly describe formose chemistry as a nonselective contributor rather than a direct valine route). This reaction is included as a literature-consistent feeder to acetaldehyde, not as a claimed selective source of isobutyraldehyde."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "NiS-like sulfide mineral aldol diversification from acetaldehyde to trace branched aldehydes including isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "transition-metal sulfide mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic or geothermal pools, concentrating episodes, low selectivity, branched products are minor"}, "mechanism": "Surface-bound acetaldehyde undergoes enolization, aldol diversification, fragmentation, and rearrangement within complex aldehyde networks to furnish low-yield branched C4 aldehydes including isobutyraldehyde.", "reasoning": "The research report identifies branched aldehyde generation as the central bottleneck and specifically points to aldol diversification on NiS catalysts as one of the most promising routes, while emphasizing poor selectivity for isobutyraldehyde (Preiner et al., 2023). This reaction is therefore explicitly low-flux and bottleneck-limited, matching the literature rather than overstating plausibility."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Spark/discharge-radical route to isobutyraldehyde in atmospheric product mixtures", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003", "mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral capture/concentration after atmospheric discharge chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "lightning/spark discharge or volcanic electrical activity; reducing gas mixtures; dissolution into surface waters"}, "mechanism": "Atmospheric radical recombination produces complex aldehyde mixtures including rare branched aldehydes; mineral-bearing surface pools capture the products together with HCN for downstream Strecker chemistry.", "reasoning": "Valine in Miller-Urey-type experiments is explained by radical chemistry generating branched aldehydes among complex product mixtures; improved analyses confirmed valine in archived discharge samples (Keefe, Newton, and Miller, 1995; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011). This step follows the report's conclusion that spark discharge is one of the few experimentally supported contexts where the valine precursor plausibly appears."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Classical Strecker formation of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-323K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surfaces in aqueous solution", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH ~9, free NH3 available, mild temperatures, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Isobutyraldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine/Schiff base, followed by cyanide addition to produce 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the best-established prebiotic route to valine and uses the exact key precursor identified in the literature. The mechanism and pH dependence are directly supported by Strecker analyses and computational free-energy studies (Miller and Van Trump, 1981; Keefe, Newton, and Miller, 1995; Devergne et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis through amide intermediate; irreversible product-forming step"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis through an amide intermediate irreversibly yields racemic valine, pulling the Strecker equilibrium forward.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of the aminonitrile is the irreversible driving step in Strecker valine formation and is well established experimentally and theoretically (Miller and Van Trump, 1981; Devergne et al., 2021). Aminonitrile persistence and hydrolysis timescales are also discussed by Miller (1998)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs-type bridge from isobutyraldehyde to alpha-ketoisovalerate/valine manifold", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted concentration in aqueous pool chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "CO2-present, cyanide/ammonia-rich solution; hydantoin-accessible chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde-derived cyanide/ammonia chemistry under CO2-rich conditions accesses hydantoin-related intermediates that bridge Strecker chemistry and alpha-keto-acid/alpha-amino-acid manifolds.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti et al. (2022) showed that Bucherer-Bergs chemistry provides a bridge between aldehyde-based Strecker reactions and alpha-keto acid metabolism through hydantoin intermediates. This node is included to connect the validated aldehyde route to the keto-acid branch without inventing an unrelated pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Protometabolic condensation from pyruvate to alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated prebiotic pools or mineral interfaces; metabolically congruent but experimentally unresolved for selective prebiotic flux"}, "mechanism": "Non-enzymatic carbon-carbon bond formation within protometabolic keto-acid chemistry yields the branched alpha-keto acid alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate-centered carbonyl networks.", "reasoning": "The report identifies alpha-ketoisovalerate as a metabolically congruent alternative precursor whose prebiotic formation could arise from pyruvate-centered condensation chemistry analogous to modern acetolactate logic, or broader non-enzymatic Krebs-like chemistry, but notes that direct experimental demonstration remains incomplete. This reaction is therefore explicitly speculative but literature-motivated and necessary to connect the reductive amination branch (Muchowska, Varma, and Moran, 2019; Copley, Smith, and Morowitz, 2005; the review findings)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Mineral-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-363K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "FeS/pyrite or related iron-bearing reductive mineral system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline pH ~8-11, anoxic, H2-bearing vent or vent-derived interface; extension of demonstrated keto-acid reductive amination chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-ketoisovalerate forms an imine with ammonia and is reduced on iron-bearing mineral surfaces to valine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is experimentally demonstrated on FeS/H2S, Fe(OH)2-derived systems, mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides, pyrite-related minerals, and metallic Ni; extension to alpha-ketoisovalerate is explicitly supported in principle by the literature although not always tested as the exact substrate (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber and Wachtershauser, 2003; Barge et al., 2019; Kaur et al., 2024; Nature Communications, 2024 pyrite photocatalysis). This is a literature-supported alternative entry to valine."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Cyanosulfidic surface chemistry feeding shared HCN and small aldehyde pools", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "cyanide-sulfide-phosphate photoredox network on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, H2S/Cu photoredox style chemistry, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "HCN-centered photoredox chemistry in the presence of sulfide and phosphate yields reactive C1-C2 carbonyl and amidine/imine intermediates that reinforce Strecker-accessible feedstock pools.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated unified cyanosulfidic chemistry generating nucleotide, lipid, and amino-acid precursor pools from HCN, H2S, UV, and phosphate. The review emphasizes that published schemes mainly build C1-C3 products and do not directly furnish valine's branched precursor; accordingly this reaction only feeds the shared HCN/small-aldehyde pool rather than claiming direct valine synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Aminonitrile preservation by formamide/formylating pool chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_013", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "formamide-rich transient drying pools; protection against Strecker reversal"}, "mechanism": "Formamide-enabled N-formylation/protection chemistry stabilizes aminonitrile pools against reversal, increasing persistence until hydrolysis to amino acid occurs.", "reasoning": "Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, 2023) showed that N-formylation of aminonitriles in formamide solvent can protect aminonitriles from reversion of Strecker equilibrium. This does not create a new molecule node here, but it provides a literature-based persistence pathway that supports downstream valine formation."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Wet-dry clay-assisted peptide capture of valine into short peptides", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "373-393K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling in mineral-rich surface pools; concentration-driven condensation"}, "mechanism": "Repeated drying and rehydration drives ester-amide exchange and peptide bond formation, trapping valine into small peptides that stabilize localized product pools.", "reasoning": "Wet-dry cycling is a well-supported downstream fate for amino acids in prebiotic pools and is especially relevant for converting low concentrations into retained oligomers (Forsythe et al., 2015; Campbell et al., 2019). This reaction places valine in the broader biochemical/prebiotic network rather than as an isolated endpoint."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Classical Strecker from atmospheric isobutyraldehyde", "description": "Spark/discharge chemistry generates HCN and rare isobutyraldehyde; surface Strecker chemistry gives valine aminonitrile, followed by hydrolysis to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Aldol-diversification Strecker route", "description": "Surface small-carbonyl chemistry generates acetaldehyde from formaldehyde, then low-yield branched aldehyde formation feeds the Strecker route to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface Strecker route via pyruvate-centered carbon fixation", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation produces pyruvate and reduced carbon that feed surface carbonyl pools, eventually yielding isobutyraldehyde and valine by Strecker chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Cyanosulfidic-assisted Strecker route", "description": "HCN-rich cyanosulfidic surface chemistry reinforces formaldehyde and acetaldehyde supply, increasing flux into the branched aldehyde bottleneck and then through Strecker chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_013", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs bridge to valine from isobutyraldehyde", "description": "Isobutyraldehyde enters a CO2-assisted Bucherer-Bergs/Strecker manifold that bridges aldehyde chemistry and keto-acid chemistry before yielding valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination from alpha-ketoisovalerate", "description": "Alpha-ketoisovalerate formed in protometabolic chemistry undergoes mineral-catalyzed reductive amination at alkaline vent interfaces to produce valine directly.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Vent-to-protometabolic keto-acid route", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation gives pyruvate, which enters protometabolic condensation to alpha-ketoisovalerate and then reductive amination to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Atmospheric aldehyde plus keto-acid convergence route", "description": "Acetaldehyde from surface photochemistry converges with hydrothermal pyruvate to form alpha-ketoisovalerate, followed by reductive amination to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id