{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T14:37:05.264287", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Valine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Valine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of valine: routes, evidence, and unresolved challenges\n\n**The Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde, HCN, and ammonia remains the most experimentally validated prebiotic route to valine**, yet the availability of the branched-chain aldehyde precursor constitutes the central bottleneck in the entire pathway. Valine (2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid, C\u2085H\u2081\u2081NO\u2082) has been confirmed in reanalyzed Miller-Urey spark discharge samples, detected at **~300\u20131,000 ppb in the Murchison meteorite** as a racemic mixture, and shown to be thermodynamically favorable for synthesis under moderate hydrothermal conditions. Despite this convergent evidence for abiotic formation, prebiotic valine production yields remain far below those of simpler amino acids like glycine, and the selective prebiotic generation of its branched C\u2084 aldehyde precursor from simple feedstocks (H\u2082O, CO\u2082, NH\u2083, HCN, CH\u2084) has never been cleanly demonstrated. This report synthesizes the full landscape of known synthesis routes, experimental evidence, environmental constraints, catalytic requirements, and open problems relevant to incorporating valine into prebiotic synthesis network models.\n\n---\n\n## Seven distinct routes connect simple molecules to valine\n\nThe literature documents multiple pathways from prebiotic feedstocks to valine, though they vary enormously in experimental support and plausibility. The dominant and best-characterized route is the **Strecker synthesis**, while several alternative pathways offer complementary or supporting roles.\n\n**Strecker synthesis.** The most established pathway proceeds in three steps. First, isobutyraldehyde ((CH\u2083)\u2082CHCHO) reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base). Second, HCN adds nucleophilically to the imine, producing 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (the \u03b1-aminonitrile intermediate). Third, hydrolysis of the nitrile group through an amide intermediate yields racemic DL-valine. The reaction proceeds optimally in aqueous solution at **pH ~9** (where free NH\u2083 is available, pK\u2090 = 9.2) and mild temperatures. The equilibration steps are reversible, but hydrolysis is irreversible, driving the reaction forward. Miller and Van Trump (1981, *Origin of Life*) established this as the operative mechanism in spark discharge experiments, and Keefe, Newton, and Miller (1995, *Nature*) confirmed isobutyraldehyde as the specific Strecker aldehyde precursor for valine. Devergne, Magrino, Pietrucci, and Saitta (2021, *Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters*) computed the full free-energy landscape of the Strecker mechanism from first principles, confirming its thermodynamic feasibility. A variant pathway, the **Bucherer-Bergs reaction**, proceeds through hydantoin intermediates when CO\u2082 is present alongside HCN and NH\u2083, bridging aldehyde-based Strecker chemistry with \u03b1-keto acid metabolism (Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy, 2022, *Nature Chemistry*).\n\n**Miller-Urey spark discharge.** Electric discharges through reducing gas mixtures (CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082, H\u2082O) generate HCN and various aldehydes in the gas phase, which dissolve and undergo Strecker chemistry in the aqueous reservoir. While Miller's original 1953 paper (*Science*) reported only five amino acids using crude paper chromatography, modern reanalyses by Bada's group confirmed valine among **22 amino acids** in the volcanic apparatus samples (Johnson et al., 2008, *Science*) and **23 amino acids** in the H\u2082S-enriched experiment (Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*). Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *PNAS*) had earlier confirmed all coded \u03b1-amino acids including valine using improved gas compositions.\n\n**Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate.** The keto acid pathway \u2014 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + NH\u2083 + 2[H] \u2192 valine + H\u2082O \u2014 parallels biological valine biosynthesis. Hafenbradl, Keller, W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, and Stetter (1995, *Tetrahedron Letters*) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids using FeS/H\u2082S as the reducing system coupled with pyrite formation. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, *Tetrahedron Letters*) revisited the reaction with freshly precipitated FeS or Fe(OH)\u2082. Most recently, Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS*) achieved reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide minerals at alkaline pH, and Kaur, Rauscher, Werner, and colleagues (2024, *Chem*) drove the reductive amination of six biological keto acids using H\u2082 on metallic nickel catalyst at 22\u00b0C and pH 8. Although \u03b1-ketoisovalerate specifically was not always the test substrate, the chemistry extends in principle to the valine precursor.\n\n**Cyanosulfidic chemistry.** Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*) demonstrated a unified protometabolic network producing precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids from HCN, H\u2082S, and phosphate under UV irradiation with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. The system generates Strecker aminonitrile precursors for **six proteinogenic amino acids**, but the reductive homologation chemistry primarily builds C\u2081\u2013C\u2083 aldehydes. **Valine's branched C\u2084 aldehyde precursor is not directly produced** in published cyanosulfidic schemes, though Sutherland's \"flow chemistry\" model envisions geochemical streams where aldol condensation could extend the carbon chain.\n\n**Fischer-Tropsch type (FTT) synthesis** at hydrothermal vents \u2014 CO + H\u2082 on Fe/Ni catalysts at 150\u2013300\u00b0C \u2014 primarily generates hydrocarbons, fatty acids, and alcohols (McCollom, Ritter, and Simoneit, 1999, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*). FTT reactions are more relevant to generating aldehyde precursors that could then feed Strecker chemistry than to directly producing amino acids. **HCN oligomerization** yields predominantly glycine and alanine upon hydrolysis (Ferris, Joshi, Edelson, and Lawless, 1978, *Journal of Molecular Evolution*); valine is not a significant product because the polymer structure favors linear, small amino acids. **Formose-type chemistry** from formaldehyde produces hydroxylated sugars and branched ketoses but not the non-hydroxylated branched aldehydes required for valine synthesis, though side reactions under basic conditions generate complex aldehyde mixtures that could include trace isobutyraldehyde.\n\n---\n\n## The isobutyraldehyde bottleneck and other critical intermediates\n\nThe central challenge in prebiotic valine synthesis is not the Strecker reaction itself \u2014 which proceeds readily when all reactants are present \u2014 but rather the upstream generation of the branched C\u2084 aldehyde precursor isobutyraldehyde from simpler molecules. This bottleneck distinguishes valine from simpler amino acids like glycine (from formaldehyde) and alanine (from acetaldehyde), whose aldehyde precursors are far more abundant in prebiotic scenarios.\n\n**Isobutyraldehyde formation** has been proposed through several routes, none fully satisfactory. Aldol condensation of acetaldehyde \u2014 itself readily formed from ethanol oxidation or spark discharge chemistry \u2014 can produce branched C\u2083\u2013C\u2084 species, but selectivity for isobutyraldehyde is poor. Preiner et al. (2023, *Nature Communications*) demonstrated that NiS-catalyzed acetylene chemistry produces acetaldehyde which undergoes aldol diversification to higher aldehydes including branched species. In spark discharge experiments, radical recombination processes (CH\u2083\u2022 combining with CHO-containing fragments) generate branched aldehydes among a complex product mixture, explaining how valine appears in Miller-Urey experiments. Decarboxylation of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate provides another route but simply shifts the precursor problem one step back. The statistical and kinetic disfavoring of branching over linear chain extension in abiotic aldol chemistry means that **isobutyraldehyde concentrations would have been orders of magnitude lower** than those of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde under any plausible prebiotic scenario.\n\n**\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate (3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid)** serves as an alternative entry point to valine through reductive amination, bypassing the Strecker pathway entirely. Its prebiotic formation could proceed through condensation reactions of pyruvate with acetaldehyde, paralleling the biological acetolactate synthase pathway, or through non-enzymatic Krebs cycle analogs (Muchowska, Varma, and Moran, 2019, *Nature*). Copley, Smith, and Morowitz (2005, *PNAS*) proposed that dinucleotide cofactors could catalyze amino acid formation from \u03b1-keto acids. Krishnamurthy's group recently demonstrated abiotic generation of \u03b1-keto acids from amino acids via phosphorylation and \u03b2-elimination, coupled with transamination (2025, *PMC*). These pathways are metabolically congruent \u2014 they mirror modern biosynthetic logic \u2014 but prebiotic availability of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate itself remains experimentally undemonstrated.\n\nThe **\u03b1-aminonitrile intermediate** (2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile) is well-characterized. Miller (1998) estimated half-lives for aminonitrile hydrolysis at **less than 1,000 years at 0\u00b0C**, accelerating dramatically at higher temperatures. Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, 2023, *JACS*) showed that N-formylation of aminonitriles in formamide solvent protects them from reversion of the Strecker equilibrium, potentially improving amino acid yields.\n\nHCN and ammonia, the two other essential Strecker reactants, face their own availability constraints. Miyakawa et al. (2002) estimated steady-state oceanic HCN at **2 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2076 M at pH 8 and 0\u00b0C**, dropping to **7 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 M at 100\u00b0C** due to hydrolysis. Ammonia concentrations in prebiotic oceans are estimated at **10\u207b\u2075 to 10\u207b\u00b3 M**. Both reagents compete across multiple reaction pathways, further limiting flux through the valine-specific Strecker channel.\n\n---\n\n## Alkaline vents and evaporitic pools offer the most plausible settings\n\nThe environmental context for prebiotic valine synthesis is constrained by a fundamental tension: higher temperatures accelerate both synthesis and decomposition, creating a narrow productive window. Two environments emerge as most favorable, each suited to different steps in the pathway.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents (Lost City type)** provide the strongest thermodynamic case. Operating at **40\u201390\u00b0C and pH 9\u201311**, these systems generate abundant H\u2082 through serpentinization of olivine, creating reducing conditions that thermodynamically favor organic synthesis. Amend and Shock (1998, *Science*) calculated that autotrophic synthesis of all 20 proteinogenic amino acids, including valine, is **exergonic under hot, moderately reduced hydrothermal conditions** but endergonic in cold surface seawater. Martin and Russell (2007, *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B*) proposed that pH and redox gradients at the vent-ocean interface could drive a primitive acetyl-CoA pathway with reductive amination as the amino acid synthesis step. Microporous chimney structures provide natural compartmentalization that concentrates reactants. Iron oxyhydroxide minerals, Fe(II)-bearing sulfides, and saponite clays present at these vents serve as catalysts. M\u00e9nez et al. (2018, *Nature*) documented abiotic formation of tryptophan in serpentinites beneath the Atlantis Massif, catalyzed by iron-rich saponite clay \u2014 the first field evidence for abiotic amino acid synthesis in a hydrothermal system.\n\n**Black smoker vents (>300\u00b0C, pH 2\u20133)** are far less favorable. Miller and Bada (1988, *Nature*) demonstrated that amino acids are **irreversibly destroyed at 240\u00b0C**, with decomposition rates vastly exceeding synthesis rates at black smoker temperatures. However, rapid cold-quenching effects in flow reactors can preserve amino acid aggregates even after brief (**2-minute**) exposure at 200\u2013250\u00b0C (Chandru, Imai, Kaneko, Obayashi, and Kobayashi, 2013, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*), suggesting that transit through high-temperature zones followed by rapid cooling could preserve products.\n\n**Surface evaporitic pools and warm little ponds** complement vent synthesis by providing concentration and polymerization. Wet-dry cycling drives condensation reactions that produce peptide bonds \u2014 Forsythe et al. (2015, *Angewandte Chemie*) demonstrated ester-mediated amide bond formation through this mechanism. Campbell et al. (2019, *Nature Communications*) showed that deliquescent minerals (K\u207a/Na\u207a salts) mediate glycine oligomerization during wet-dry cycles at 100\u2013120\u00b0C, yielding oligomers **over 10-fold higher than controls**. UV radiation in the absence of an ozone layer is a double-edged factor: it drives photochemistry producing HCN and aldehydes but also degrades amino acids. Urea-containing pools can produce carbamoyl amino acids with ~100% yield under UV, providing protective derivatization (2023, *Earth and Planetary Science Letters*).\n\nThe **optimal temperature window for prebiotic valine synthesis** is likely **50\u2013150\u00b0C**, balancing synthesis rate against decomposition. Hydrophobic amino acids including valine are generally more thermally stable than hydrophilic ones like serine and aspartic acid (Sato et al., 2004). Li and Brill (2003) measured valine decarboxylation rates at 310\u2013330\u00b0C comparable to those of leucine and isoleucine, while Pietrucci and Aponte et al. (2018, *ACS Earth and Space Chemistry*) computed decomposition rates of **10\u207b\u00b9\u00b9 to 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 s\u207b\u00b9 at 100\u00b0C**, corresponding to half-lives of **~1,000 to tens of thousands of years**.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts bridge thermodynamic gaps and concentrate products\n\nThree classes of minerals play distinct roles in prebiotic valine chemistry: iron-sulfur phases drive redox reactions, clay minerals concentrate and polymerize products, and semiconductor minerals enable photocatalysis.\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** form the catalytic backbone of W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world hypothesis. Pyrite formation (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + 2H\u207a + 2e\u207b) provides reducing equivalents for organic synthesis. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (*Science*, 1997; 1998; 2003) demonstrated activated acetic acid synthesis from CO + CH\u2083SH on (Fe,Ni)S, peptide formation from amino acids activated with CO on (Ni,Fe)S at 100\u00b0C, and reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids with freshly precipitated FeS. A 2024 study in *Nature Communications* revealed that natural pyrite surfaces exhibit **photocatalytic reductive amination** of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids with D-enantiomeric excesses of **14.5\u201342.4%**, driven by the wavy atomic arrangement of the pyrite surface. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), structurally analogous to biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] ferredoxin clusters (Russell et al., 1994), and mackinawite (FeS) serve as additional catalytic phases. Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS*) showed that the **Fe(II):Fe(III) ratio** in mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides is a critical parameter determining whether reductive amination (producing amino acids) or reduction (producing hydroxy acids) dominates.\n\n**Clay minerals**, particularly montmorillonite, serve primarily as concentration and polymerization agents. Montmorillonite-catalyzed oligomerization of activated monomers proceeds **100\u20131,000 times faster** than hydrolysis (Kawamura and Ferris, 1994), and Ferris et al. (1996, *Nature*) produced oligomers up to **55 monomers** on mineral surfaces. For amino acids specifically, cation exchange is the dominant adsorption mechanism, with cationic amino acids (arginine, lysine) adsorbed with Langmuir constants **30\u201350\u00d7 greater** than zwitterionic species like valine (Millman et al., 2024, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*). Iron-rich saponite clay catalyzes Friedel-Crafts reactions that produce aromatic amino acids in serpentinites (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018, *Nature*). Layered double hydroxides facilitate prebiotic peptide formation with a ribosome-like catalytic mechanism, where hydrophobic amino acids including valine aggregate within clay layers enabling peptide hydrophobic collapse (*Nature Communications*, 2017).\n\n**Semiconductor minerals** enable photocatalytic pathways. ZnS drives reversible amination of \u03b1-oxo acids to amino acids on photo-illuminated surfaces (Wang et al., 2012, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*) and catalyzes three of five steps in the reverse TCA cycle, achieving **95% yield** for fumarate-to-succinate conversion (Guzman and Martin, 2016). Chiral mesostructured ZnS can drive enantioselective amino acid synthesis from CO\u2082 reduction (2024, *ScienceDirect*). TiO\u2082, the most active photocatalytic semiconductor in Earth's crust (0.01\u20131 wt%), catalyzes C\u2013C bond formation and conversion of formamide to nucleobases (Saladino et al., 2006, *PNAS*), with negligible temperature dependence allowing product accumulation without thermal decomposition.\n\n---\n\n## From Miller's spark flask to Murchison: converging experimental evidence\n\nLaboratory experiments and meteoritic analyses provide complementary lines of evidence for abiotic valine formation, though quantitative yields remain modest.\n\n**Miller-Urey experiments** tell a story of improving analytical sensitivity revealing increasing molecular diversity. Miller's 1953 classic experiment identified only five amino acids. When Bada's group reanalyzed Miller's archived samples using HPLC-FD and LC-ToF-MS, the volcanic apparatus yielded **22 amino acids including valine** (Johnson et al., 2008, *Science*), and the 1958 H\u2082S experiment produced **23 amino acids** with dramatically enhanced alkyl amino acid yields (Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*). The H\u2082S samples showed amino acid yields **several hundred times larger** than the original and volcanic experiments for some species. All amino acids were racemic, confirming abiotic origin. Glycine yields reach ~2.1% of input carbon in the classic apparatus; valine yields are roughly **~0.04\u20130.05% of carbon**, approximately 5% the yield of glycine.\n\n**Proton and photon irradiation experiments** expand the energy source repertoire. Kobayashi et al. (2023, *Life*) showed that **2.5 MeV proton irradiation** (simulating galactic cosmic rays) produces amino acids from CO\u2082 + CH\u2084 + N\u2082 + H\u2082O mixtures even at methane ratios as low as **0.5%**, whereas spark discharges require \u226515% methane and UV irradiation produces no amino acids even at 50% methane. Nuevo et al. (2008, *Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society*) detected 13 amino acids including valine from UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene in H\u2082O + NH\u2083 ice at 15 K, demonstrating interstellar ice processing as a viable amino acid source.\n\n**Meteoritic detection** provides the strongest evidence for widespread abiotic amino acid synthesis. Kvenvolden et al. (1970, *Nature*) first identified valine in the Murchison meteorite as **nearly equal D and L enantiomers**. Cronin and Pizzarello (1983, *Advances in Space Research*) expanded the Murchison amino acid inventory to 52 species. Valine concentrations in Murchison range from **~300 to 1,000 ppb**, compared to glycine at 3,000\u20136,000 ppb and \u03b1-aminoisobutyric acid (a non-protein amino acid) at even higher levels. Pizzarello and Cronin (2000, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*) confirmed that valine in meteorites is **essentially racemic** (D/L \u2248 1.0), in stark contrast to its structural analog isovaline, which shows L-enantiomeric excesses up to **18.5 \u00b1 2.4%** in Murchison (Glavin and Dworkin, 2009, *PNAS*). Valine has been confirmed in Murchison, Murray, Orgueil, and Aguas Zarcas meteorites, with amino acid abundance decreasing systematically with increasing carbon number and structural complexity \u2014 consistent with Strecker synthesis from a distribution of available aldehydes.\n\n**Extraterrestrial in situ detections** remain limited. Only glycine has been confirmed in cometary material \u2014 at comet Wild 2 by Stardust (Elsila et al., 2009) and at comet 67P by Rosetta/ROSINA (Altwegg et al., 2016, *Science Advances*). No amino acids, including valine, have been definitively detected on Mars; SAM on Curiosity found chlorinated organics but perchlorates complicate amino acid preservation and detection.\n\n---\n\n## Five fundamental challenges define the frontier\n\nDespite substantial progress, prebiotic valine synthesis faces five interconnected challenges that remain actively debated.\n\n**The branched-precursor problem** is paramount. No known efficient prebiotic pathway selectively generates isobutyraldehyde or \u03b1-ketoisovalerate from C\u2081 feedstocks. Formaldehyde and acetaldehyde \u2014 precursors to glycine and alanine \u2014 are among the most abundant products of atmospheric photochemistry, spark discharges, and interstellar chemistry. Isobutyraldehyde requires a specific branching event that is kinetically disfavored relative to linear chain extension. This thermodynamic and kinetic asymmetry explains why valine yields are consistently **5\u201310% those of glycine** across all experimental systems. The most promising avenues involve aldol diversification on NiS catalysts (Preiner et al., 2023), radical recombination in reducing atmospheres (Parker et al., 2011), or meteoritic/cometary delivery of complex aldehyde mixtures.\n\n**The homochirality problem** remains unsolved. All known abiotic synthesis routes produce racemic valine, yet biology uses exclusively L-valine. Proposed symmetry-breaking mechanisms include circularly polarized light producing >1.3% enantiomeric excess in ice analogs (de Marcellus et al., 2011), pyrite photocatalysis generating 14.5\u201342.4% D-amino acid excess (*Nature Communications*, 2024), and the CISS (Chiral-Induced Spin Selectivity) effect on magnetized magnetite surfaces (Ozturk et al., 2022, *PNAS*). A 2025 proposal (*PNAS*) suggests homochirality emerged network-wide through CISS-induced ee on magnetite, amplified by conglomerate crystallization of ribo-aminooxazoline to 100% ee, then propagated to amino acids. Notably, valine itself may not undergo efficient chiral selection on calcite crystal faces because its side chain provides insufficient configuration-dependent interaction points for the three-point binding rule (Hazen et al., 2001, *PNAS*).\n\n**The concentration problem** is severe for all amino acids but especially for lower-yield species like valine. Even optimistic prebiotic scenarios yield oceanic amino acid concentrations far below those needed for polymerization. Evaporative concentration in tidal pools, mineral surface adsorption, eutectic freezing in ice (where HCN polymerization proceeds efficiently at \u22122\u00b0C), and aerosol enrichment (10\u00b2\u201310\u2074 fold) have all been proposed. Black et al. (2019, *PNAS*) showed that transiently concentrated amino acids from drying bind to and stabilize fatty acid membranes, with stabilization persisting after redilution. Tectonic fault zone vesicles at ~1 km depth may selectively trap hydrophobic amino acids like valine (Mayer et al., 2017, *Life*).\n\n**Thermal decomposition** constrains all high-temperature scenarios. Valine decomposes via parallel decarboxylation (\u2192 isobutylamine + CO\u2082) and deamination (\u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + NH\u2083) pathways. At 100\u00b0C, half-lives are estimated at **~10\u00b3\u201310\u2074 years**; at 250\u00b0C, amino acids degrade to less than 1% within **25 hours** (Lemke et al., 2009). Miller and Bada's (1988) demonstration that amino acids are irreversibly destroyed at 240\u00b0C remains a foundational constraint on black smoker origin scenarios, though rapid transit with cold quenching could preserve products formed during brief high-temperature exposure.\n\n**Competition for shared reactants** limits valine's share of the product distribution. HCN, NH\u2083, and reducing equivalents are consumed by all Strecker pathways simultaneously; more abundant aldehyde precursors (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde) outcompete isobutyraldehyde for these shared reagents. Side reactions including Cannizzaro disproportionation of isobutyraldehyde to isobutanol and isobutyric acid, and aldol condensation to higher products, further reduce the flux toward valine. The consistent amino acid distribution pattern \u2014 glycine >> alanine >> valine \u2014 observed across spark discharge experiments, meteorites, and theoretical models reflects these fundamental constraints.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nPrebiotic valine synthesis sits at a revealing intersection of established chemistry and persistent challenges. The Strecker pathway is mechanistically well-understood and experimentally confirmed across multiple independent systems \u2014 from Miller's spark flask to carbonaceous meteorites. Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on iron-containing minerals offers a metabolically congruent alternative that connects prebiotic chemistry directly to extant biosynthetic logic. Alkaline hydrothermal vents provide the most thermodynamically favorable environment, while surface evaporitic pools offer the concentration and cycling dynamics needed for downstream polymerization.\n\nThe critical insight for prebiotic network design is that **valine's synthesis bottleneck is not the amino acid-forming reaction itself but the upstream generation of its branched C\u2084 precursor**. This contrasts sharply with glycine and alanine, where precursor availability is not limiting. Any realistic prebiotic synthesis network must therefore include explicit pathways for branched aldehyde or branched keto acid generation \u2014 likely through aldol diversification on transition metal sulfide catalysts, radical chemistry in reducing atmospheres, or meteoritic/cometary delivery. The consistent ~20-fold yield deficit of valine relative to glycine across all experimental systems quantifies the kinetic cost of molecular branching and should be incorporated as a constraint in network flux models. The racemic nature of meteoritic valine, the unresolved homochirality problem, and the narrow thermal stability window (50\u2013150\u00b0C optimal) further define the parameter space within which any viable prebiotic scenario must operate.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.81\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong: it is connected, has sufficient node counts, uses multiple hubs, and includes genuine convergence around HCN, acetaldehyde, isobutyraldehyde, alpha-ketoisovalerate, and the valine aminonitrile. It also succeeds in showing Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow, which is one of its major strengths. The best-supported chemistry is the classical Strecker route from isobutyraldehyde to valine aminonitrile and then valine, plus the general concept of reductive amination from alpha-ketoisovalerate. The biggest issue is literature alignment and chemical precision in the upstream branched-precursor chemistry. The research strongly emphasizes that isobutyraldehyde formation is the central unresolved bottleneck, and several network reactions treat its production too optimistically. Additional weaknesses include an implausible or oversimplified formaldehyde-to-acetaldehyde step, a compressed Bucherer-Bergs bridge, and a vague aminonitrile preservation self-loop. Mineral-agent compliance is mixed: most hydrothermal and surface reactions appear to invoke minerals, but some agents are not ideal matches to the required set or to the cited literature. Overall, the network is viable as a high-level synthesis network to valine and captures the literature's main logic, but several individual reactions should be downgraded as low-yield, speculative, or overcompressed.\n- Issues: ['The downstream Strecker chemistry is sound, but the route from formaldehyde to acetaldehyde and then to branched aldehydes is weak. Formose chemistry does not cleanly produce acetaldehyde-rich pools, and the conversion of acetaldehyde to isobutyraldehyde is possible only as poorly selective diversification chemistry. The pathway captures a literature-discussed possibility but overstates the directness of the upstream carbonyl sequence.', 'This pathway does a good job of linking hydrothermal C1/C3 fixation to surface Strecker chemistry, which is a major strength of the network. However, the pyruvate-producing hydrothermal step is somewhat compressed and literature support for direct pyruvate formation under the stated conditions is weaker than for formate/acetate. The main weakness remains the surface carbonyl sequence to isobutyraldehyde, especially the formaldehyde-to-acetaldehyde conversion.', \"The network correctly invokes cyanosulfidic chemistry as a source of HCN and small aldehydes, but the literature specifically notes that published cyanosulfidic schemes do not directly generate valine's branched C4 aldehyde precursor. The pathway therefore works only if supplemented by another source of isobutyraldehyde. The endgame is sound, but the 'cyanosulfidic-assisted' framing is stronger than the literature supports.\", 'This pathway is conceptually attractive because it connects aldehyde chemistry to the keto-acid manifold, in line with literature discussion of Bucherer-Bergs chemistry. However, the single reaction that outputs both alpha-ketoisovalerate and valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde, NH3, HCN, and CO2 is overly compressed and not chemically clean as written. The final reductive amination step is plausible in principle, but the bridge reaction needs better specification.', 'The terminal reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine is literature-aligned in broad terms. The problem is the upstream production of alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and acetaldehyde in a single protometabolic condensation step; this is only weakly supported and likely oversimplified relative to acetolactate-like chemistry or broader nonenzymatic metabolic networks. As a result, the pathway is plausible in concept but insufficiently substantiated in execution.', 'This pathway has good metabolic logic, moving from hydrothermal carbon fixation to pyruvate and onward to a branched keto acid, then valine. It aligns with the literature emphasis on a keto-acid alternative to Strecker synthesis. However, both pyruvate formation and especially alpha-ketoisovalerate formation are underspecified and more speculative than the terminal reductive amination. This makes the route interesting but not yet strongly convincing.', 'This integrated convergence pathway is topologically attractive because it merges atmospheric aldehyde chemistry with hydrothermal keto-acid chemistry. Still, its chemistry depends heavily on the compressed Bucherer-Bergs bridge and on optimistic treatment of branched precursor availability. The cross-environment design is strong, but the specific transformations need tighter mechanistic grounding.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network targets valine through two literature-grounded core routes: (1) the best-supported Strecker sequence from isobutyraldehyde via the valine aminonitrile, and (2) reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate on iron-bearing minerals. The network explicitly treats branched-precursor generation as the main bottleneck, so upstream routes to isobutyraldehyde and alpha-ketoisovalerate are marked as low-yield or speculative where the literature identifies them as unresolved. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon hubs such as formate, acetate, acetaldehyde, and pyruvate, while surface chemistry supplies HCN, NH3-rich alkaline conditions, UV-driven cyanosulfidic products, and concentration through evaporitic settings. Biochemical/prebiotic stages then connect keto-acid and amino-acid manifolds through transamination, hydrolysis, and peptide assembly. Ten distinct pathways are enumerated by recombining convergent routes through the hub molecules HCN, acetaldehyde, isobutyraldehyde, alpha-ketoisovalerate, and valine aminonitrile.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid/formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetic acid/acetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid/pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-4(2)3-5/h3-4H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoisovaleric acid/alpha-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(6)3-7/h4-5H,6H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,4-imidazolidinedione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydantoin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4N2O2/c6-2-4-1-5-3(2)7/h1H2,(H2,4,5,6,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"sulfane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent setting, pH 9-11, anoxic, H2-rich serpentinization fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface CO2 activation followed by hydrogenation to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents and release of formate into aqueous phase.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on Fe-S minerals is a core iron-sulfur-world transformation and is consistent with alkaline vent models in which H2-rich fluids reduce CO2 on greigite/mackinawite-like surfaces; these conditions align with vent thermodynamics for amino-acid precursor generation (Martin & Russell, 2007; Russell et al., 1994; Amend & Shock, 1998).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Magnetite-mediated carbon fixation from formate toward pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor or alkaline vent analog, reducing conditions; this step is a compressed network representation of hydrothermal alpha-keto-acid generation and should be treated as low-yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive reductive carboxylation and C-C bond-forming steps on mixed Fe oxide/metal surfaces generate a C3 alpha-keto acid pool represented here by pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is a plausible hydrothermal keto-acid hub in nonenzymatic protometabolic networks, but direct formation under the stated conditions is less well established than formate or acetate. This reaction is included as a necessary low-yield connector to the keto-acid manifold and is grounded in hydrothermal protometabolism studies rather than a single clean pyruvate synthesis experiment (Muchowska, Varma, & Moran, 2019; Amend & Shock, 1998).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of acetaldehyde from C1 feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"423-573K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydrothermal FTT-like conditions; aldehydes arise as minor oxygenated products in complex mixtures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface CO/CO2 hydrogenation on iron-bearing minerals gives mixed reduced carbon products including oxygenates such as aldehydes, represented here by acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FTT-type hydrothermal chemistry is experimentally linked mainly to hydrocarbons, alcohols, and oxygenated organics rather than direct amino acid synthesis; acetaldehyde is therefore represented as a plausible minor product feeding later surface chemistry, not as a selective major product (McCollom, Ritter, & Simoneit, 1999).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface UV generation of HCN from reduced atmospheric chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals under UV irradiation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subaerial geothermal fields or evaporitic pool margins, strong UV, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical redox cycling in reduced C/N systems generates cyanide that accumulates in surface waters during irradiation and concentration cycles.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is a central prebiotic feedstock in surface photochemistry and cyanosulfidic networks. While atmospheric energy sources include lightning and UV, semiconductor-assisted photochemistry is a valid mineral-coupled surface representation for HCN accumulation in prebiotic settings (Patel et al., 2015; Miyakawa et al., 2002; Saladino et al., 2006).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydration to formamide under UV-active surface conditions\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV exposure in shallow pools; formamide acts as a preserving and activating medium\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydration and photochemical conversion of cyanide leads to formamide accumulation in concentrated surface films or pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a documented product and medium in prebiotic UV chemistry and is relevant because aminonitrile N-formylation in formamide can protect against reverse Strecker equilibration. The TiO2-formamide linkage is literature-grounded for prebiotic photocatalysis (Saladino et al., 2006; Green, Xu, & Sutherland, 2021; Green, Xu, & Sutherland, 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol diversification to branched aldehydes including isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"transition-metal sulfide surfaces with wet-dry concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"low-selectivity diversification chemistry in evaporitic pools; branched products expected only in minor amounts\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation/diversification of small aldehydes produces a complex mixture of higher carbonyl compounds, with rare branching events yielding isobutyraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies isobutyraldehyde formation as the key unresolved bottleneck. Published work supports aldehyde diversification to higher and branched aldehydes from acetaldehyde-rich systems, but not selective or high-yield production. This step is therefore explicitly low-yield and bottlenecked (Preiner et al., 2023; Parker et al., 2011; Keefe, Newton, & Miller, 1995).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical Strecker formation of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration on phosphate and clay surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous solution at pH about 9 where free NH3 is available; evaporitic concentration enhances flux\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Isobutyraldehyde forms an imine with NH3, followed by nucleophilic cyanide addition to produce the alpha-aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the most experimentally validated prebiotic route to valine. Isobutyraldehyde is the specific Strecker aldehyde precursor for valine, and the aminonitrile intermediate is well established. Mild alkaline aqueous conditions are literature-supported (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Keefe, Newton, & Miller, 1995; Devergne, Magrino, Pietrucci, & Saitta, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis through amide intermediates; irreversible step drives Strecker sequence forward\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile to the alpha-amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis is the irreversible driving step of Strecker amino-acid synthesis and is specifically established for valine chemistry; hydrolysis rates increase strongly with temperature while remaining compatible with geologic timescales at lower temperatures (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Devergne et al., 2021; Miller, 1998).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs-type bridge from Strecker aldehyde chemistry toward a keto-acid precursor manifold\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate-rich evaporitic concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"CO2-present Bucherer-Bergs-like chemistry; represented as a network bridge rather than a single clean one-pot transformation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbonyl-ammonia-cyanide chemistry in the presence of CO2 accesses hydantoin intermediates that connect aldehyde-based Strecker chemistry to the alpha-keto-acid manifold; the network records both hydantoin and alpha-ketoisovalerate as reachable states.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature explicitly notes that Bucherer-Bergs chemistry can bridge aldehyde-based Strecker reactions with alpha-keto-acid metabolism via hydantoins. Because the exact valine-specific prebiotic sequence is not fully resolved, this node is included as a partially speculative but literature-motivated bridge and is intentionally marked as a compressed network connector (Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, & Krishnamurthy, 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Protometabolic generation of alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"nonenzymatic protometabolic condensation in concentrated pools or interfaces; low-yield and unresolved\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"C-C bond formation from a pyruvate-centered keto-acid network generates a branched C5 alpha-keto acid pool represented by alpha-ketoisovalerate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies alpha-ketoisovalerate as a metabolically congruent entry point to valine and suggests pyruvate plus acetaldehyde condensation as a plausible nonenzymatic analogue of modern valine biosynthesis, but emphasizes that prebiotic availability of alpha-ketoisovalerate remains experimentally unresolved. This reaction is therefore included as speculative but necessary (Muchowska, Varma, & Moran, 2019; Copley, Smith, & Morowitz, 2005).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Iron-sulfur or Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"fresh FeS/pyrite-forming system with H2/H2S; literature also supports metallic Ni at 22C and pH 8\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline to near-neutral reducing conditions; product distribution depends on Fe(II):Fe(III) balance\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Keto acid undergoes imine formation with ammonia followed by mineral-mediated reduction to the alpha-amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on iron-bearing minerals is experimentally supported and provides the metabolically congruent alternative route to valine. Although alpha-ketoisovalerate was not always the exact tested substrate, the chemistry extends in principle to the valine precursor. FeS/H2S and freshly precipitated FeS systems support the general transformation, with modern confirmation that H2 on metallic Ni can reduce multiple biological keto acids (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber & Wachtersh\u00e4user, 2003; Barge et al., 2019; Kaur et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination equilibrium between alpha-ketoisovalerate and valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral interfaces or concentrated pools; network bookkeeping node for bidirectional amino acid/keto acid manifold connectivity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reversible amino-group transfer conceptually links alpha-ketoisovalerate and valine pools within a broader nonenzymatic amino acid/keto acid network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies transamination and alpha-keto-acid/amino-acid interconversion as important in metabolically congruent prebiotic chemistry. This reaction is included as a schematic equilibrium connector to reflect that broader network logic rather than as a single fully resolved valine-specific experiment (Copley, Smith, & Morowitz, 2005; 2025 PMC report cited in the research findings).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Strecker from hydrothermal acetaldehyde diversification\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon generates acetaldehyde, which diversifies on surface sulfide-rich settings to trace isobutyraldehyde, then undergoes classical Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2-to-formate-supported Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction populates reduced carbon pools that feed pyruvate/acetaldehyde chemistry; acetaldehyde then reaches isobutyraldehyde and enters the validated Strecker endgame.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN-enabled direct Strecker branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface photochemistry supplies HCN while hydrothermal acetaldehyde diversification supplies isobutyraldehyde; these converge in the classical valine aminonitrile route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-assisted Strecker preservation route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN first accesses formamide-rich surface chemistry, supporting aminonitrile persistence, then the standard Strecker sequence proceeds from isobutyraldehyde to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs bridge from branched aldehyde to alpha-ketoisovalerate then valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Trace isobutyraldehyde enters a CO2-containing Bucherer-Bergs-like manifold producing hydantoin-linked intermediates and a keto-acid branch, then reductive amination yields valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal keto-acid route from pyruvate\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate reduction feeds pyruvate, pyruvate and acetaldehyde enter a speculative protometabolic condensation to alpha-ketoisovalerate, and hydrothermal reductive amination furnishes valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-centered metabolically congruent route\",\n      \"description\": \"A pyruvate hub formed in hydrothermal settings is funneled into alpha-ketoisovalerate in concentrated prebiotic pools and then reduced to valine on iron-sulfur minerals.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent HCN and alpha-keto acid dual-entry route\",\n      \"description\": \"One branch forms valine aminonitrile by Strecker chemistry while another independently forms alpha-ketoisovalerate; both converge on the same target through hydrolysis or reductive amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Bottleneck-explicit branched aldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"This pathway isolates the key literature bottleneck: low-yield surface formation of isobutyraldehyde from acetaldehyde, followed by the validated Strecker chemistry to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Integrated hydrothermal-surface-biochemical network route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction produces reduced carbon hubs; surface photochemistry produces HCN and concentration; hydrothermal and surface branches jointly feed both Strecker and keto-acid channels to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets valine through two literature-grounded core routes: (1) the best-supported Strecker sequence from isobutyraldehyde via the valine aminonitrile, and (2) reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate on iron-bearing minerals. The network explicitly treats branched-precursor generation as the main bottleneck, so upstream routes to isobutyraldehyde and alpha-ketoisovalerate are marked as low-yield or speculative where the literature identifies them as unresolved. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon hubs such as formate, acetate, acetaldehyde, and pyruvate, while surface chemistry supplies HCN, NH3-rich alkaline conditions, UV-driven cyanosulfidic products, and concentration through evaporitic settings. Biochemical/prebiotic stages then connect keto-acid and amino-acid manifolds through transamination, hydrolysis, and peptide assembly. Ten distinct pathways are enumerated by recombining convergent routes through the hub molecules HCN, acetaldehyde, isobutyraldehyde, alpha-ketoisovalerate, and valine aminonitrile.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetic acid/acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid/pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-4(2)3-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoisovaleric acid/alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "valine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(6)3-7/h4-5H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H6N2O2", "iupac_name": "2,4-imidazolidinedione", "common_name": "hydantoin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4N2O2/c6-2-4-1-5-3(2)7/h1H2,(H2,4,5,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent setting, pH 9-11, anoxic, H2-rich serpentinization fluids"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface CO2 activation followed by hydrogenation to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents and release of formate into aqueous phase.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on Fe-S minerals is a core iron-sulfur-world transformation and is consistent with alkaline vent models in which H2-rich fluids reduce CO2 on greigite/mackinawite-like surfaces; these conditions align with vent thermodynamics for amino-acid precursor generation (Martin & Russell, 2007; Russell et al., 1994; Amend & Shock, 1998)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Magnetite-mediated carbon fixation from formate toward pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor or alkaline vent analog, reducing conditions; this step is a compressed network representation of hydrothermal alpha-keto-acid generation and should be treated as low-yield"}, "mechanism": "Successive reductive carboxylation and C-C bond-forming steps on mixed Fe oxide/metal surfaces generate a C3 alpha-keto acid pool represented here by pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is a plausible hydrothermal keto-acid hub in nonenzymatic protometabolic networks, but direct formation under the stated conditions is less well established than formate or acetate. This reaction is included as a necessary low-yield connector to the keto-acid manifold and is grounded in hydrothermal protometabolism studies rather than a single clean pyruvate synthesis experiment (Muchowska, Varma, & Moran, 2019; Amend & Shock, 1998)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of acetaldehyde from C1 feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "423-573K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "hydrothermal FTT-like conditions; aldehydes arise as minor oxygenated products in complex mixtures"}, "mechanism": "Surface CO/CO2 hydrogenation on iron-bearing minerals gives mixed reduced carbon products including oxygenates such as aldehydes, represented here by acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "FTT-type hydrothermal chemistry is experimentally linked mainly to hydrocarbons, alcohols, and oxygenated organics rather than direct amino acid synthesis; acetaldehyde is therefore represented as a plausible minor product feeding later surface chemistry, not as a selective major product (McCollom, Ritter, & Simoneit, 1999)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface UV generation of HCN from reduced atmospheric chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals under UV irradiation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subaerial geothermal fields or evaporitic pool margins, strong UV, anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical redox cycling in reduced C/N systems generates cyanide that accumulates in surface waters during irradiation and concentration cycles.", "reasoning": "HCN is a central prebiotic feedstock in surface photochemistry and cyanosulfidic networks. While atmospheric energy sources include lightning and UV, semiconductor-assisted photochemistry is a valid mineral-coupled surface representation for HCN accumulation in prebiotic settings (Patel et al., 2015; Miyakawa et al., 2002; Saladino et al., 2006)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "HCN hydration to formamide under UV-active surface conditions", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV exposure in shallow pools; formamide acts as a preserving and activating medium"}, "mechanism": "Hydration and photochemical conversion of cyanide leads to formamide accumulation in concentrated surface films or pools.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a documented product and medium in prebiotic UV chemistry and is relevant because aminonitrile N-formylation in formamide can protect against reverse Strecker equilibration. The TiO2-formamide linkage is literature-grounded for prebiotic photocatalysis (Saladino et al., 2006; Green, Xu, & Sutherland, 2021; Green, Xu, & Sutherland, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Aldol diversification to branched aldehydes including isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "transition-metal sulfide surfaces with wet-dry concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "low-selectivity diversification chemistry in evaporitic pools; branched products expected only in minor amounts"}, "mechanism": "Condensation/diversification of small aldehydes produces a complex mixture of higher carbonyl compounds, with rare branching events yielding isobutyraldehyde.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies isobutyraldehyde formation as the key unresolved bottleneck. Published work supports aldehyde diversification to higher and branched aldehydes from acetaldehyde-rich systems, but not selective or high-yield production. This step is therefore explicitly low-yield and bottlenecked (Preiner et al., 2023; Parker et al., 2011; Keefe, Newton, & Miller, 1995)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Classical Strecker formation of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-323K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration on phosphate and clay surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous solution at pH about 9 where free NH3 is available; evaporitic concentration enhances flux"}, "mechanism": "Isobutyraldehyde forms an imine with NH3, followed by nucleophilic cyanide addition to produce the alpha-aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the most experimentally validated prebiotic route to valine. Isobutyraldehyde is the specific Strecker aldehyde precursor for valine, and the aminonitrile intermediate is well established. Mild alkaline aqueous conditions are literature-supported (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Keefe, Newton, & Miller, 1995; Devergne, Magrino, Pietrucci, & Saitta, 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis through amide intermediates; irreversible step drives Strecker sequence forward"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile to the alpha-amino acid.", "reasoning": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis is the irreversible driving step of Strecker amino-acid synthesis and is specifically established for valine chemistry; hydrolysis rates increase strongly with temperature while remaining compatible with geologic timescales at lower temperatures (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Devergne et al., 2021; Miller, 1998)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs-type bridge from Strecker aldehyde chemistry toward a keto-acid precursor manifold", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-rich evaporitic concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "CO2-present Bucherer-Bergs-like chemistry; represented as a network bridge rather than a single clean one-pot transformation"}, "mechanism": "Carbonyl-ammonia-cyanide chemistry in the presence of CO2 accesses hydantoin intermediates that connect aldehyde-based Strecker chemistry to the alpha-keto-acid manifold; the network records both hydantoin and alpha-ketoisovalerate as reachable states.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly notes that Bucherer-Bergs chemistry can bridge aldehyde-based Strecker reactions with alpha-keto-acid metabolism via hydantoins. Because the exact valine-specific prebiotic sequence is not fully resolved, this node is included as a partially speculative but literature-motivated bridge and is intentionally marked as a compressed network connector (Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, & Krishnamurthy, 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Protometabolic generation of alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "nonenzymatic protometabolic condensation in concentrated pools or interfaces; low-yield and unresolved"}, "mechanism": "C-C bond formation from a pyruvate-centered keto-acid network generates a branched C5 alpha-keto acid pool represented by alpha-ketoisovalerate.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies alpha-ketoisovalerate as a metabolically congruent entry point to valine and suggests pyruvate plus acetaldehyde condensation as a plausible nonenzymatic analogue of modern valine biosynthesis, but emphasizes that prebiotic availability of alpha-ketoisovalerate remains experimentally unresolved. This reaction is therefore included as speculative but necessary (Muchowska, Varma, & Moran, 2019; Copley, Smith, & Morowitz, 2005)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Iron-sulfur or Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "fresh FeS/pyrite-forming system with H2/H2S; literature also supports metallic Ni at 22C and pH 8", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline to near-neutral reducing conditions; product distribution depends on Fe(II):Fe(III) balance"}, "mechanism": "Keto acid undergoes imine formation with ammonia followed by mineral-mediated reduction to the alpha-amino acid.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on iron-bearing minerals is experimentally supported and provides the metabolically congruent alternative route to valine. Although alpha-ketoisovalerate was not always the exact tested substrate, the chemistry extends in principle to the valine precursor. FeS/H2S and freshly precipitated FeS systems support the general transformation, with modern confirmation that H2 on metallic Ni can reduce multiple biological keto acids (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber & Wachtersh\u00e4user, 2003; Barge et al., 2019; Kaur et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Trans