  \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.71,\n      \"feedback\": \"This route aligns with the literature in spirit: hydrothermal carbon fixation to pyruvate followed by metabolically congruent alpha-ketoisovalerate formation and reductive amination. The weakness is that abiotic generation of alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and acetaldehyde is not experimentally established in the simple one-step form presented. Reductive amination itself is plausible on FeS/H2S or Ni catalysts, but substrate-specific support for alpha-ketoisovalerate remains indirect.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Treat alpha-ketoisovalerate formation as speculative and possibly multi-step, not a single direct coupling.\",\n        \"Specify alkaline vent-like conditions for reductive amination, closer to the literature-supported 40-90C to moderate-temperature window rather than generic hydrothermal.\",\n        \"Separate strong evidence for reductive amination from weak evidence for precursor generation.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.38,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.78\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.57,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.67,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.76,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.8,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.66,\n      \"feedback\": \"This short protometabolic route is attractive conceptually because it mirrors extant biosynthesis, but its key bond-forming step to alpha-ketoisovalerate is the least validated part of the network. Reductive amination is reasonable; precursor synthesis is not. As a hypothesis-generating branch it is useful, but it is not sufficiently evidenced for approval.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n    