est pathway in the set. It correctly centers the upstream branched aldehyde supply as the limiting issue, while keeping the validated Strecker and hydrolysis chemistry intact. It still falls short of approval because the actual source of isobutyraldehyde remains too weakly justified in the network.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_006\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Anchor isobutyraldehyde production to specific low-selectivity branched aldehyde mixtures from NiS-catalyzed acetylene/acetaldehyde chemistry or spark discharge evidence.\",\n        \"Quantify that this route is likely low flux relative to glycine/alanine channels.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.4,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.38,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.78\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.61,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.91,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the best overall network route in terms of environmental interconnection and target access. It successfully combines hydrothermal reduced-carbon generation, surface cyanide/Strecker chemistry, and biochemical completion. However, it still depends on speculative branched precursor generation and an under-defined alpha-ketoisovalerate formation step. Strong network design, moderate chemical support.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Keep this as the flagship route, but revise weak upstream steps to align tightly with literature-supported low-temperature alkaline vent and surface scenarios.\",\n        \"Add explicit mineral assignments for each surface and hydrothermal reaction if missing in the full schema.\",\n        \"Include literature citations per reaction in the final network JSON reasoning fields.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is topologically strong and chemically mixed. It satisfies the broad architectural goals: enough molecule and reaction nodes, multiple hubs, several convergence points, and clear Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical flow. It also correctly identifies the central literature insight that valine synthesis is limited not by the Strecker or reductive amination steps themselves, but by poor prebiotic access to branched precursors such as isobutyraldehyde and likely alpha-ketoisovalerate. The best-supported chemistry in the network is rxn_001 (CO2 to formate), rxn_007 (Strecker valine aminonitrile formation), rxn_008 (aminonitrile hydrolysis to valine), and rxn_011 (reductive amination in principle on FeS/H2S or Ni systems). The weakest chemistry is the direct HCN source rxn_004, branched aldehyde formation rxn_006, the over-condensed Bucherer-Bergs bridge rxn_009, and the direct pyruvate-plus-acetaldehyde to alpha-ketoisovalerate step rxn_010. Literature alignment is partial rather than strong: the network captures the major experimentally supported endgame but compresses or invents upstream steps beyond what the cited literature firmly establishes. It also omits reaction-level citations and detailed mineral-agent specification required by the synthesis schema. Overall this is a coherent and useful hypothesis network, but not yet an approved high-confidence synthesis network because too much of the valine-specific upstream chemistry remains speculative or underspecified.\",\n  \"approved\": false,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.88,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.84\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores":