n_010. Literature alignment is partial rather than strong: the network captures the major experimentally supported endgame but compresses or invents upstream steps beyond what the cited literature firmly establishes. It also omits reaction-level citations and detailed mineral-agent specification required by the synthesis schema. Overall this is a coherent and useful hypothesis network, but not yet an approved high-confidence synthesis network because too much of the valine-specific upstream chemistry remains speculative or underspecified.", "approved": false, "hub_quality": 0.88, "convergence_quality": 0.84}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 67618.26205253601, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T14:40:01.161505", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Valine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Valine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of valine: routes, evidence, and unresolved challenges\n\n**The Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde, HCN, and ammonia remains the most experimentally validated prebiotic route to valine**, yet the availability of the branched-chain aldehyde precursor constitutes the central bottleneck in the entire pathway. Valine (2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid, C\u2085H\u2081\u2081NO\u2082) has been confirmed in reanalyzed Miller-Urey spark discharge samples, detected at **~300\u20131,000 ppb in the Murchison meteorite** as a racemic mixture, and shown to be thermodynamically favorable for synthesis under moderate hydrothermal conditions. Despite this convergent evidence for abiotic formation, prebiotic valine production yields remain far below those of simpler amino acids like glycine, and the selective prebiotic generation of its branched C\u2084 aldehyde precursor from simple feedstocks (H\u2082O, CO\u2082, NH\u2083, HCN, CH\u2084) has never been cleanly demonstrated. This report synthesizes the full landscape of known synthesis routes, experimental evidence, environmental constraints, catalytic requirements, and open problems relevant to incorporating valine into prebiotic synthesis network models.\n\n---\n\n## Seven distinct routes connect simple molecules to valine\n\nThe literature documents multiple pathways from prebiotic feedstocks to valine, though they vary enormously in experimental support and plausibility. The dominant and best-characterized route is the **Strecker synthesis**, while several alternative pathways offer complementary or supporting roles.\n\n**Strecker synthesis.** The most established pathway proceeds in three steps. First, isobutyraldehyde ((CH\u2083)\u2082CHCHO) reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base). Second, HCN adds nucleophilically to the imine, producing 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (the \u03b1-aminonitrile intermediate). Third, hydrolysis of the nitrile group through an amide intermediate yields racemic DL-valine. The reaction proceeds optimally in aqueous solution at **pH ~9** (where free NH\u2083 is available, pK\u2090 = 9.2) and mild temperatures. The equilibration steps are reversible, but hydrolysis is irreversible, driving the reaction forward. Miller and Van Trump (1981, *Origin of Life*) established this as the operative mechanism in spark discharge experiments, and Keefe, Newton, and Miller (1995, *Nature*) confirmed isobutyraldehyde as the specific Strecker aldehyde precursor for valine. Devergne, Magrino, Pietrucci, and Saitta (2021, *Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters*) computed the full free-energy landscape of the Strecker mechanism from first principles, confirming its thermodynamic feasibility. A variant pathway, the **Bucherer-Bergs reaction**, proceeds through hydantoin intermediates when CO\u2082 is present alongside HCN and NH\u2083, bridging aldehyde-based Strecker chemistry with \u03b1-keto acid metabolism (Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy, 2022, *Nature Chemistry*).\n\n**Miller-Urey spark discharge.** Electric discharges through reducing gas mixtures (CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082, H\u2082O) generate HCN and various aldehydes in the gas phase, which dissolve and undergo Strecker chemistry in the aqueous reservoir. While Miller's original 1953 paper (*Science*) reported only five amino acids using crude paper chromatography, modern reanalyses by Bada's group confirmed valine among **22 amino acids** in the volcanic apparatus samples (Johnson et al., 2008, *Science*) and **23 amino acids** in the H\u2082S-enriched experiment (Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*). Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *PNAS*) had earlier confirmed all coded \u03b1-amino acids including valine using improved gas compositions.\n\n**Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate.** The keto acid pathway \u2014 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + NH\u2083 + 2[H] \u2192 valine + H\u2082O \u2014 parallels biological valine biosynthesis. Hafenbradl, Keller, W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, and Stetter (1995, *Tetrahedron Letters*) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids using FeS/H\u2082S as the reducing system coupled with pyrite formation. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, *Tetrahedron Letters*) revisited the reaction with freshly precipitated FeS or Fe(OH)\u2082. Most recently, Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS*) achieved reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide minerals at alkaline pH, and Kaur, Rauscher, Werner, and colleagues (2024, *Chem*) drove the reductive amination of six biological keto acids using H\u2082 on metallic nickel catalyst at 22\u00b0C and pH 8. Although \u03b1-ketoisovalerate specifically was not always the test substrate, the chemistry extends in principle to the valine precursor.\n\n**Cyanosulfidic chemistry.** Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*) demonstrated a unified protometabolic network producing precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids from HCN, H\u2082S, and phosphate under UV irradiation with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. The system generates Strecker aminonitrile precursors for **six proteinogenic amino acids**, but the reductive homologation chemistry primarily builds C\u2081\u2013C\u2083 aldehydes. **Valine's branched C\u2084 aldehyde precursor is not directly produced** in published cyanosulfidic schemes, though Sutherland's \"flow chemistry\" model envisions geochemical streams where aldol condensation could extend the carbon chain.\n\n**Fischer-Tropsch type (FTT) synthesis** at hydrothermal vents \u2014 CO + H\u2082 on Fe/Ni catalysts at 150\u2013300\u00b0C \u2014 primarily generates hydrocarbons, fatty acids, and alcohols (McCollom, Ritter, and Simoneit, 1999, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*). FTT reactions are more relevant to generating aldehyde precursors that could then feed Strecker chemistry than to directly producing amino acids. **HCN oligomerization** yields predominantly glycine and alanine upon hydrolysis (Ferris, Joshi, Edelson, and Lawless, 1978, *Journal of Molecular Evolution*); valine is not a significant product because the polymer structure favors linear, small amino acids. **Formose-type chemistry** from formaldehyde produces hydroxylated sugars and branched ketoses but not the non-hydroxylated branched aldehydes required for valine synthesis, though side reactions under basic conditions generate complex aldehyde mixtures that could include trace isobutyraldehyde.\n\n---\n\n## The isobutyraldehyde bottleneck and other critical intermediates\n\nThe central challenge in prebiotic valine synthesis is not the Strecker reaction itself \u2014 which proceeds readily when all reactants are present \u2014 but rather the upstream generation of the branched C\u2084 aldehyde precursor isobutyraldehyde from simpler molecules. This bottleneck distinguishes valine from simpler amino acids like glycine (from formaldehyde) and alanine (from acetaldehyde), whose aldehyde precursors are far more abundant in prebiotic scenarios.\n\n**Isobutyraldehyde formation** has been proposed through several routes, none fully satisfactory. Aldol condensation of acetaldehyde \u2014 itself readily formed from ethanol oxidation or spark discharge chemistry \u2014 can produce branched C\u2083\u2013C\u2084 species, but selectivity for isobutyraldehyde is poor. Preiner et al. (2023, *Nature Communications*) demonstrated that NiS-catalyzed acetylene chemistry produces acetaldehyde which undergoes aldol diversification to higher aldehydes including branched species. In spark discharge experiments, radical recombination processes (CH\u2083\u2022 combining with CHO-containing fragments) generate branched aldehydes among a complex product mixture, explaining how valine appears in Miller-Urey experiments. Decarboxylation of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate provides another route but simply shifts the precursor problem one step back. The statistical and kinetic disfavoring of branching over linear chain extension in abiotic aldol chemistry means that **isobutyraldehyde concentrations would have been orders of magnitude lower** than those of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde under any plausible prebiotic scenario.\n\n**\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate (3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid)** serves as an alternative entry point to valine through reductive amination, bypassing the Strecker pathway entirely. Its prebiotic formation could proceed through condensation reactions of pyruvate with acetaldehyde, paralleling the biological acetolactate synthase pathway, or through non-enzymatic Krebs cycle analogs (Muchowska, Varma, and Moran, 2019, *Nature*). Copley, Smith, and Morowitz (2005, *PNAS*) proposed that dinucleotide cofactors could catalyze amino acid formation from \u03b1-keto acids. Krishnamurthy's group recently demonstrated abiotic generation of \u03b1-keto acids from amino acids via phosphorylation and \u03b2-elimination, coupled with transamination (2025, *PMC*). These pathways are metabolically congruent \u2014 they mirror modern biosynthetic logic \u2014 but prebiotic availability of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate itself remains experimentally undemonstrated.\n\nThe **\u03b1-aminonitrile intermediate** (2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile) is well-characterized. Miller (1998) estimated half-lives for aminonitrile hydrolysis at **less than 1,000 years at 0\u00b0C**, accelerating dramatically at higher temperatures. Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, 2023, *JACS*) showed that N-formylation of aminonitriles in formamide solvent protects them from reversion of the Strecker equilibrium, potentially improving amino acid yields.\n\nHCN and ammonia, the two other essential Strecker reactants, face their own availability constraints. Miyakawa et al. (2002) estimated steady-state oceanic HCN at **2 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2076 M at pH 8 and 0\u00b0C**, dropping to **7 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 M at 100\u00b0C** due to hydrolysis. Ammonia concentrations in prebiotic oceans are estimated at **10\u207b\u2075 to 10\u207b\u00b3 M**. Both reagents compete across multiple reaction pathways, further limiting flux through the valine-specific Strecker channel.\n\n---\n\n## Alkaline vents and evaporitic pools offer the most plausible settings\n\nThe environmental context for prebiotic valine synthesis is constrained by a fundamental tension: higher temperatures accelerate both synthesis and decomposition, creating a narrow productive window. Two environments emerge as most favorable, each suited to different steps in the pathway.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents (Lost City type)** provide the strongest thermodynamic case. Operating at **40\u201390\u00b0C and pH 9\u201311**, these systems generate abundant H\u2082 through serpentinization of olivine, creating reducing conditions that thermodynamically favor organic synthesis. Amend and Shock (1998, *Science*) calculated that autotrophic synthesis of all 20 proteinogenic amino acids, including valine, is **exergonic under hot, moderately reduced hydrothermal conditions** but endergonic in cold surface seawater. Martin and Russell (2007, *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B*) proposed that pH and redox gradients at the vent-ocean interface could drive a primitive acetyl-CoA pathway with reductive amination as the amino acid synthesis step. Microporous chimney structures provide natural compartmentalization that concentrates reactants. Iron oxyhydroxide minerals, Fe(II)-bearing sulfides, and saponite clays present at these vents serve as catalysts. M\u00e9nez et al. (2018, *Nature*) documented abiotic formation of tryptophan in serpentinites beneath the Atlantis Massif, catalyzed by iron-rich saponite clay \u2014 the first field evidence for abiotic amino acid synthesis in a hydrothermal system.\n\n**Black smoker vents (>300\u00b0C, pH 2\u20133)** are far less favorable. Miller and Bada (1988, *Nature*) demonstrated that amino acids are **irreversibly destroyed at 240\u00b0C**, with decomposition rates vastly exceeding synthesis rates at black smoker temperatures. However, rapid cold-quenching effects in flow reactors can preserve amino acid aggregates even after brief (**2-minute**) exposure at 200\u2013250\u00b0C (Chandru, Imai, Kaneko, Obayashi, and Kobayashi, 2013, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*), suggesting that transit through high-temperature zones followed by rapid cooling could preserve products.\n\n**Surface evaporitic pools and warm little ponds** complement vent synthesis by providing concentration and polymerization. Wet-dry cycling drives condensation reactions that produce peptide bonds \u2014 Forsythe et al. (2015, *Angewandte Chemie*) demonstrated ester-mediated amide bond formation through this mechanism. Campbell et al. (2019, *Nature Communications*) showed that deliquescent minerals (K\u207a/Na\u207a salts) mediate glycine oligomerization during wet-dry cycles at 100\u2013120\u00b0C, yielding oligomers **over 10-fold higher than controls**. UV radiation in the absence of an ozone layer is a double-edged factor: it drives photochemistry producing HCN and aldehydes but also degrades amino acids. Urea-containing pools can produce carbamoyl amino acids with ~100% yield under UV, providing protective derivatization (2023, *Earth and Planetary Science Letters*).\n\nThe **optimal temperature window for prebiotic valine synthesis** is likely **50\u2013150\u00b0C**, balancing synthesis rate against decomposition. Hydrophobic amino acids including valine are generally more thermally stable than hydrophilic ones like serine and aspartic acid (Sato et al., 2004). Li and Brill (2003) measured valine decarboxylation rates at 310\u2013330\u00b0C comparable to those of leucine and isoleucine, while Pietrucci and Aponte et al. (2018, *ACS Earth and Space Chemistry*) computed decomposition rates of **10\u207b\u00b9\u00b9 to 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 s\u207b\u00b9 at 100\u00b0C**, corresponding to half-lives of **~1,000 to tens of thousands of years**.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts bridge thermodynamic gaps and concentrate products\n\nThree classes of minerals play distinct roles in prebiotic valine chemistry: iron-sulfur phases drive redox reactions, clay minerals concentrate and polymerize products, and semiconductor minerals enable photocatalysis.\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** form the catalytic backbone of W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world hypothesis. Pyrite formation (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + 2H\u207a + 2e\u207b) provides reducing equivalents for organic synthesis. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (*Science*, 1997; 1998; 2003) demonstrated activated acetic acid synthesis from CO + CH\u2083SH on (Fe,Ni)S, peptide formation from amino acids activated with CO on (Ni,Fe)S at 100\u00b0C, and reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids with freshly precipitated FeS. A 2024 study in *Nature Communications* revealed that natural pyrite surfaces exhibit **photocatalytic reductive amination** of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids with D-enantiomeric excesses of **14.5\u201342.4%**, driven by the wavy atomic arrangement of the pyrite surface. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), structurally analogous to biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] ferredoxin clusters (Russell et al., 1994), and mackinawite (FeS) serve as additional catalytic phases. Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS*) showed that the **Fe(II):Fe(III) ratio** in mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides is a critical parameter determining whether reductive amination (producing amino acids) or reduction (producing hydroxy acids) dominates.\n\n**Clay minerals**, particularly montmorillonite, serve primarily as concentration and polymerization agents. Montmorillonite-catalyzed oligomerization of activated monomers proceeds **100\u20131,000 times faster** than hydrolysis (Kawamura and Ferris, 1994), and Ferris et al. (1996, *Nature*) produced oligomers up to **55 monomers** on mineral surfaces. For amino acids specifically, cation exchange is the dominant adsorption mechanism, with cationic amino acids (arginine, lysine) adsorbed with Langmuir constants **30\u201350\u00d7 greater** than zwitterionic species like valine (Millman et al., 2024, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*). Iron-rich saponite clay catalyzes Friedel-Crafts reactions that produce aromatic amino acids in serpentinites (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018, *Nature*). Layered double hydroxides facilitate prebiotic peptide formation with a ribosome-like catalytic mechanism, where hydrophobic amino acids including valine aggregate within clay layers enabling peptide hydrophobic collapse (*Nature Communications*, 2017).\n\n**Semiconductor minerals** enable photocatalytic pathways. ZnS drives reversible amination of \u03b1-oxo acids to amino acids on photo-illuminated surfaces (Wang et al., 2012, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*) and catalyzes three of five steps in the reverse TCA cycle, achieving **95% yield** for fumarate-to-succinate conversion (Guzman and Martin, 2016). Chiral mesostructured ZnS can drive enantioselective amino acid synthesis from CO\u2082 reduction (2024, *ScienceDirect*). TiO\u2082, the most active photocatalytic semiconductor in Earth's crust (0.01\u20131 wt%), catalyzes C\u2013C bond formation and conversion of formamide to nucleobases (Saladino et al., 2006, *PNAS*), with negligible temperature dependence allowing product accumulation without thermal decomposition.\n\n---\n\n## From Miller's spark flask to Murchison: converging experimental evidence\n\nLaboratory experiments and meteoritic analyses provide complementary lines of evidence for abiotic valine formation, though quantitative yields remain modest.\n\n**Miller-Urey experiments** tell a story of improving analytical sensitivity revealing increasing molecular diversity. Miller's 1953 classic experiment identified only five amino acids. When Bada's group reanalyzed Miller's archived samples using HPLC-FD and LC-ToF-MS, the volcanic apparatus yielded **22 amino acids including valine** (Johnson et al., 2008, *Science*), and the 1958 H\u2082S experiment produced **23 amino acids** with dramatically enhanced alkyl amino acid yields (Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*). The H\u2082S samples showed amino acid yields **several hundred times larger** than the original and volcanic experiments for some species. All amino acids were racemic, confirming abiotic origin. Glycine yields reach ~2.1% of input carbon in the classic apparatus; valine yields are roughly **~0.04\u20130.05% of carbon**, approximately 5% the yield of glycine.\n\n**Proton and photon irradiation experiments** expand the energy source repertoire. Kobayashi et al. (2023, *Life*) showed that **2.5 MeV proton irradiation** (simulating galactic cosmic rays) produces amino acids from CO\u2082 + CH\u2084 + N\u2082 + H\u2082O mixtures even at methane ratios as low as **0.5%**, whereas spark discharges require \u226515% methane and UV irradiation produces no amino acids even at 50% methane. Nuevo et al. (2008, *Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society*) detected 13 amino acids including valine from UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene in H\u2082O + NH\u2083 ice at 15 K, demonstrating interstellar ice processing as a viable amino acid source.\n\n**Meteoritic detection** provides the strongest evidence for widespread abiotic amino acid synthesis. Kvenvolden et al. (1970, *Nature*) first identified valine in the Murchison meteorite as **nearly equal D and L enantiomers**. Cronin and Pizzarello (1983, *Advances in Space Research*) expanded the Murchison amino acid inventory to 52 species. Valine concentrations in Murchison range from **~300 to 1,000 ppb**, compared to glycine at 3,000\u20136,000 ppb and \u03b1-aminoisobutyric acid (a non-protein amino acid) at even higher levels. Pizzarello and Cronin (2000, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*) confirmed that valine in meteorites is **essentially racemic** (D/L \u2248 1.0), in stark contrast to its structural analog isovaline, which shows L-enantiomeric excesses up to **18.5 \u00b1 2.4%** in Murchison (Glavin and Dworkin, 2009, *PNAS*). Valine has been confirmed in Murchison, Murray, Orgueil, and Aguas Zarcas meteorites, with amino acid abundance decreasing systematically with increasing carbon number and structural complexity \u2014 consistent with Strecker synthesis from a distribution of available aldehydes.\n\n**Extraterrestrial in situ detections** remain limited. Only glycine has been confirmed in cometary material \u2014 at comet Wild 2 by Stardust (Elsila et al., 2009) and at comet 67P by Rosetta/ROSINA (Altwegg et al., 2016, *Science Advances*). No amino acids, including valine, have been definitively detected on Mars; SAM on Curiosity found chlorinated organics but perchlorates complicate amino acid preservation and detection.\n\n---\n\n## Five fundamental challenges define the frontier\n\nDespite substantial progress, prebiotic valine synthesis faces five interconnected challenges that remain actively debated.\n\n**The branched-precursor problem** is paramount. No known efficient prebiotic pathway selectively generates isobutyraldehyde or \u03b1-ketoisovalerate from C\u2081 feedstocks. Formaldehyde and acetaldehyde \u2014 precursors to glycine and alanine \u2014 are among the most abundant products of atmospheric photochemistry, spark discharges, and interstellar chemistry. Isobutyraldehyde requires a specific branching event that is kinetically disfavored relative to linear chain extension. This thermodynamic and kinetic asymmetry explains why valine yields are consistently **5\u201310% those of glycine** across all experimental systems. The most promising avenues involve aldol diversification on NiS catalysts (Preiner et al., 2023), radical recombination in reducing atmospheres (Parker et al., 2011), or meteoritic/cometary delivery of complex aldehyde mixtures.\n\n**The homochirality problem** remains unsolved. All known abiotic synthesis routes produce racemic valine, yet biology uses exclusively L-valine. Proposed symmetry-breaking mechanisms include circularly polarized light producing >1.3% enantiomeric excess in ice analogs (de Marcellus et al., 2011), pyrite photocatalysis generating 14.5\u201342.4% D-amino acid excess (*Nature Communications*, 2024), and the CISS (Chiral-Induced Spin Selectivity) effect on magnetized magnetite surfaces (Ozturk et al., 2022, *PNAS*). A 2025 proposal (*PNAS*) suggests homochirality emerged network-wide through CISS-induced ee on magnetite, amplified by conglomerate crystallization of ribo-aminooxazoline to 100% ee, then propagated to amino acids. Notably, valine itself may not undergo efficient chiral selection on calcite crystal faces because its side chain provides insufficient configuration-dependent interaction points for the three-point binding rule (Hazen et al., 2001, *PNAS*).\n\n**The concentration problem** is severe for all amino acids but especially for lower-yield species like valine. Even optimistic prebiotic scenarios yield oceanic amino acid concentrations far below those needed for polymerization. Evaporative concentration in tidal pools, mineral surface adsorption, eutectic freezing in ice (where HCN polymerization proceeds efficiently at \u22122\u00b0C), and aerosol enrichment (10\u00b2\u201310\u2074 fold) have all been proposed. Black et al. (2019, *PNAS*) showed that transiently concentrated amino acids from drying bind to and stabilize fatty acid membranes, with stabilization persisting after redilution. Tectonic fault zone vesicles at ~1 km depth may selectively trap hydrophobic amino acids like valine (Mayer et al., 2017, *Life*).\n\n**Thermal decomposition** constrains all high-temperature scenarios. Valine decomposes via parallel decarboxylation (\u2192 isobutylamine + CO\u2082) and deamination (\u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + NH\u2083) pathways. At 100\u00b0C, half-lives are estimated at **~10\u00b3\u201310\u2074 years**; at 250\u00b0C, amino acids degrade to less than 1% within **25 hours** (Lemke et al., 2009). Miller and Bada's (1988) demonstration that amino acids are irreversibly destroyed at 240\u00b0C remains a foundational constraint on black smoker origin scenarios, though rapid transit with cold quenching could preserve products formed during brief high-temperature exposure.\n\n**Competition for shared reactants** limits valine's share of the product distribution. HCN, NH\u2083, and reducing equivalents are consumed by all Strecker pathways simultaneously; more abundant aldehyde precursors (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde) outcompete isobutyraldehyde for these shared reagents. Side reactions including Cannizzaro disproportionation of isobutyraldehyde to isobutanol and isobutyric acid, and aldol condensation to higher products, further reduce the flux toward valine. The consistent amino acid distribution pattern \u2014 glycine >> alanine >> valine \u2014 observed across spark discharge experiments, meteorites, and theoretical models reflects these fundamental constraints.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nPrebiotic valine synthesis sits at a revealing intersection of established chemistry and persistent challenges. The Strecker pathway is mechanistically well-understood and experimentally confirmed across multiple independent systems \u2014 from Miller's spark flask to carbonaceous meteorites. Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on iron-containing minerals offers a metabolically congruent alternative that connects prebiotic chemistry directly to extant biosynthetic logic. Alkaline hydrothermal vents provide the most thermodynamically favorable environment, while surface evaporitic pools offer the concentration and cycling dynamics needed for downstream polymerization.\n\nThe critical insight for prebiotic network design is that **valine's synthesis bottleneck is not the amino acid-forming reaction itself but the upstream generation of its branched C\u2084 precursor**. This contrasts sharply with glycine and alanine, where precursor availability is not limiting. Any realistic prebiotic synthesis network must therefore include explicit pathways for branched aldehyde or branched keto acid generation \u2014 likely through aldol diversification on transition metal sulfide catalysts, radical chemistry in reducing atmospheres, or meteoritic/cometary delivery. The consistent ~20-fold yield deficit of valine relative to glycine across all experimental systems quantifies the kinetic cost of molecular branching and should be incorporated as a constraint in network flux models. The racemic nature of meteoritic valine, the unresolved homochirality problem, and the narrow thermal stability window (50\u2013150\u00b0C optimal) further define the parameter space within which any viable prebiotic scenario must operate.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.81\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong: it is connected, has sufficient node counts, uses multiple hubs, and includes genuine convergence around HCN, acetaldehyde, isobutyraldehyde, alpha-ketoisovalerate, and the valine aminonitrile. It also succeeds in showing Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow, which is one of its major strengths. The best-supported chemistry is the classical Strecker route from isobutyraldehyde to valine aminonitrile and then valine, plus the general concept of reductive amination from alpha-ketoisovalerate. The biggest issue is literature alignment and chemical precision in the upstream branched-precursor chemistry. The research strongly emphasizes that isobutyraldehyde formation is the central unresolved bottleneck, and several network reactions treat its production too optimistically. Additional weaknesses include an implausible or oversimplified formaldehyde-to-acetaldehyde step, a compressed Bucherer-Bergs bridge, and a vague aminonitrile preservation self-loop. Mineral-agent compliance is mixed: most hydrothermal and surface reactions appear to invoke minerals, but some agents are not ideal matches to the required set or to the cited literature. Overall, the network is viable as a high-level synthesis network to valine and captures the literature's main logic, but several individual reactions should be downgraded as low-yield, speculative, or overcompressed.\n- Issues: ['The downstream Strecker chemistry is sound, but the route from formaldehyde to acetaldehyde and then to branched aldehydes is weak. Formose chemistry does not cleanly produce acetaldehyde-rich pools, and the conversion of acetaldehyde to isobutyraldehyde is possible only as poorly selective diversification chemistry. The pathway captures a literature-discussed possibility but overstates the directness of the upstream carbonyl sequence.', 'This pathway does a good job of linking hydrothermal C1/C3 fixation to surface Strecker chemistry, which is a major strength of the network. However, the pyruvate-producing hydrothermal step is somewhat compressed and literature support for direct pyruvate formation under the stated conditions is weaker than for formate/acetate. The main weakness remains the surface carbonyl sequence to isobutyraldehyde, especially the formaldehyde-to-acetaldehyde conversion.', \"The network correctly invokes cyanosulfidic chemistry as a source of HCN and small aldehydes, but the literature specifically notes that published cyanosulfidic schemes do not directly generate valine's branched C4 aldehyde precursor. The pathway therefore works only if supplemented by another source of isobutyraldehyde. The endgame is sound, but the 'cyanosulfidic-assisted' framing is stronger than the literature supports.\", 'This pathway is conceptually attractive because it connects aldehyde chemistry to the keto-acid manifold, in line with literature discussion of Bucherer-Bergs chemistry. However, the single reaction that outputs both alpha-ketoisovalerate and valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde, NH3, HCN, and CO2 is overly compressed and not chemically clean as written. The final reductive amination step is plausible in principle, but the bridge reaction needs better specification.', 'The terminal reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine is literature-aligned in broad terms. The problem is the upstream production of alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and acetaldehyde in a single protometabolic condensation step; this is only weakly supported and likely oversimplified relative to acetolactate-like chemistry or broader nonenzymatic metabolic networks. As a result, the pathway is plausible in concept but insufficiently substantiated in execution.', 'This pathway has good metabolic logic, moving from hydrothermal carbon fixation to pyruvate and onward to a branched keto acid, then valine. It aligns with the literature emphasis on a keto-acid alternative to Strecker synthesis. However, both pyruvate formation and especially alpha-ketoisovalerate formation are underspecified and more speculative than the terminal reductive amination. This makes the route interesting but not yet strongly convincing.', 'This integrated convergence pathway is topologically attractive because it merges atmospheric aldehyde chemistry with hydrothermal keto-acid chemistry. Still, its chemistry depends heavily on the compressed Bucherer-Bergs bridge and on optimistic treatment of branched precursor availability. The cross-environment design is strong, but the specific transformations need tighter mechanistic grounding.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.74\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong and chemically mixed. It satisfies the broad architectural goals: enough molecule and reaction nodes, multiple hubs, several convergence points, and clear Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical flow. It also correctly identifies the central literature insight that valine synthesis is limited not by the Strecker or reductive amination steps themselves, but by poor prebiotic access to branched precursors such as isobutyraldehyde and likely alpha-ketoisovalerate. The best-supported chemistry in the network is rxn_001 (CO2 to formate), rxn_007 (Strecker valine aminonitrile formation), rxn_008 (aminonitrile hydrolysis to valine), and rxn_011 (reductive amination in principle on FeS/H2S or Ni systems). The weakest chemistry is the direct HCN source rxn_004, branched aldehyde formation rxn_006, the over-condensed Bucherer-Bergs bridge rxn_009, and the direct pyruvate-plus-acetaldehyde to alpha-ketoisovalerate step rxn_010. Literature alignment is partial rather than strong: the network captures the major experimentally supported endgame but compresses or invents upstream steps beyond what the cited literature firmly establishes. It also omits reaction-level citations and detailed mineral-agent specification required by the synthesis schema. Overall this is a coherent and useful hypothesis network, but not yet an approved high-confidence synthesis network because too much of the valine-specific upstream chemistry remains speculative or underspecified.\n- Issues: ['This is the most literature-consistent conceptual route because it uses the validated Strecker sequence from isobutyraldehyde to valine aminonitrile to valine. The major weakness is upstream precursor supply: hydrothermal acetaldehyde formation is plausible only as a mixed low-selectivity FTT output, and conversion of acetaldehyde to isobutyraldehyde is the key unresolved bottleneck identified in the literature. HCN generation is also oversimplified relative to atmospheric discharge or cyanosulfidic scenarios. Final nitrile hydrolysis to valine is credible.', 'This route is connected and environmentally integrated, but formate-to-pyruvate chemistry is more plausible than directly necessary for the Strecker branch and does not clearly strengthen access to valine. The route inherits the same isobutyraldehyde bottleneck and weak HCN generation assumption. The pyruvate node is a good hub, but this pathway overstates support for pyruvate-centered contribution to the direct Strecker route.', \"As a streamlined Strecker route this is coherent and reaches the target through the strongest experimentally supported downstream chemistry. However, the phrase 'HCN-enabled direct Strecker branch' masks the fact that HCN availability and especially isobutyraldehyde availability are both limiting. The route is acceptable as a network branch but not strong enough for approval because the bottleneck step remains under-supported.\", 'The formamide node is literature-relevant because formylation/formamide-rich environments can help preserve aminonitriles, but in this network rxn_005 is disconnected mechanistically from the actual Strecker-to-valine sequence. As written, formamide is produced but not clearly used to protect or channel valine aminonitrile. This lowers pathway coherence despite decent chemistry for the core Strecker steps.', 'This is the weakest named route among the major target-producing branches. The Bucherer-Bergs literature does support hydantoin intermediates bridging aldehyde chemistry and amino acid/keto-acid manifolds, but the specific reaction as encoded is chemically muddled: CO2 does not simply convert the aldehyde/HCN/NH3 set into both hydantoin and alpha-ketoisovalerate in one step. The bridge is conceptually inspired by literature but insufficiently specified and over-condensed.', 'This route aligns with the literature in spirit: hydrothermal carbon fixation to pyruvate followed by metabolically congruent alpha-ketoisovalerate formation and reductive amination. The weakness is that abiotic generation of alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and acetaldehyde is not experimentally established in the simple one-step form presented. Reductive amination itself is plausible on FeS/H2S or Ni catalysts, but substrate-specific support for alpha-ketoisovalerate remains indirect.', 'This short protometabolic route is attractive conceptually because it mirrors extant biosynthesis, but its key bond-forming step to alpha-ketoisovalerate is the least validated part of the network. Reductive amination is reasonable; precursor synthesis is not. As a hypothesis-generating branch it is useful, but it is not sufficiently evidenced for approval.', \"This integrated dual-entry route captures the network's intended convergence, but it compounds all of the weak links rather than resolving them. The HCN branch, branched aldehyde branch, and keto-acid branch are all present, but two of the key convergence-forming reactions are speculative or over-compressed. Good topology, moderate chemistry.\", 'This bottleneck-explicit route is honest and nearly the strongest pathway in the set. It correctly centers the upstream branched aldehyde supply as the limiting issue, while keeping the validated Strecker and hydrolysis chemistry intact. It still falls short of approval because the actual source of isobutyraldehyde remains too weakly justified in the network.', 'This is the best overall network route in terms of environmental interconnection and target access. It successfully combines hydrothermal reduced-carbon generation, surface cyanide/Strecker chemistry, and biochemical completion. However, it still depends on speculative branched precursor generation and an under-defined alpha-ketoisovalerate formation step. Strong network design, moderate chemical support.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network is built around the literature-supported conclusion that prebiotic valine formation is best explained by two validated endgame chemistries: (i) Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde, ammonia, and hydrogen cyanide through the valine aminonitrile, and (ii) reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate on iron-sulfur or metallic catalysts. The network therefore makes the branched-precursor bottleneck explicit rather than assuming efficient production of isobutyraldehyde or alpha-ketoisovalerate. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon hubs such as formate, acetate, acetaldehyde, and pyruvate under vent-compatible iron-sulfur catalysis; surface settings supply HCN, aminonitrile formation, branched aldehyde diversification, and concentration under wet-dry and photochemical regimes; biochemical/prebiotic settings provide hydrolysis, transamination connectivity, and peptide assembly. Several pathways are intentionally low-yield or speculative where the literature identifies unresolved gaps, especially in the upstream generation of branched C4 precursors.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid/formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-4(2)3-5/h3-4H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(6)3-7/h4-5H,6H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHNO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H20N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-[(2-amino-3-methylbutanoyl)amino]-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valylvaline\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite-catalyzed reduction of carbon dioxide to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite, mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface CO2 activation followed by stepwise hydrogenation to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents and release of formate into solution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This hydrothermal entry step follows iron-sulfur vent chemistry in which greigite and related FeS phases reduce CO2 under alkaline, H2-rich conditions and is directly aligned with the required hydrothermal reaction set and iron-sulfur world models (Russell et al., 1994; Martin and Russell, 2007). It also reflects the thermodynamic favorability of amino-acid-supporting carbon fixation under hydrothermal conditions (Amend and Shock, 1998).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Iron-sulfur carbon fixation from formate/carbon monoxide to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite, pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"vent micropores, reducing conditions, acetyl-CoA-analog style carbon fixation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-bound C1 units are condensed and reduced on iron-sulfur minerals to an activated acetyl equivalent that hydrolyzes or equilibrates to acetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction represents the vent-compatible acetyl-CoA-analog carbon fixation logic emphasized for early metabolism, where FeS/NiS-like surfaces enable C1 coupling to acetyl species; acetate production is much better supported hydrothermally than direct branched intermediates and therefore serves as a realistic node feeding downstream carbonyl chemistry (Huber and Wachtershauser, 1997; Martin and Russell, 2007; Amend and Shock, 1998).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Magnetite-catalyzed Fischer-Tropsch-type formation of acetaldehyde from carbon monoxide and hydrogen\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"423-573K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite, elemental iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal or vent-associated FTT regime; low selectivity mixed carbonyl output\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO hydrogenation on metal/oxide surfaces yields a distribution of reduced carbonyls and alcohols, including low-yield acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal FTT chemistry is supported as a source of hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes rather than amino acids directly. Here acetaldehyde is treated explicitly as a low-selectivity mixed product, not a clean major output, in line with the literature caution on upstream carbonyl supply (McCollom et al., 1999). This avoids overstating formaldehyde-to-acetaldehyde chemistry criticized in previous attempts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon dioxide on iron minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite, greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent/subseafloor setting; low-to-moderate yield alpha-keto acid generation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential mineral-catalyzed reduction and C-C bond formation from CO2-derived C1 units produce alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct abiotic pyruvate generation in hydrothermal systems is less firmly established than formate or acetate, so this node is included as a plausible but comparatively weaker vent-derived metabolic hub rather than a dominant flux channel. Its inclusion is justified by the report's recognition of pyruvate-centered protometabolic chemistry and nonenzymatic carbon-fixation analogs (Muchowska et al., 2019; Amend and Shock, 1998).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-driven generation of hydrogen cyanide in surface photochemical settings\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2, sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"strong UV irradiation, anoxic atmosphere, evaporitic pool or tidal-flat photochemistry; low steady-state HCN concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox surface chemistry generates reduced C-N species and supports HCN accumulation in localized surface reservoirs.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature emphasizes HCN as essential but environmentally limited, with low steady-state concentrations and strong competition among pathways. This surface-photochemical source is therefore represented as a concentration-limited feed rather than an abundant bulk reagent, consistent with atmospheric/photochemical interpretations and cyanosulfidic frameworks (Miyakawa et al., 2002; Patel et al., 2015; Saladino et al., 2006).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydration of hydrogen cyanide to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2, phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed shallow pools; formamide-rich microenvironments possible during evaporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes hydration to formamide, aided by photochemical activation and concentration on mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is included because the research specifically highlights formamide/N-formylation chemistry as protective for aminonitriles and relevant to surface prebiotic photochemistry. TiO2-mediated formamide chemistry is well established in prebiotic studies (Saladino et al., 2006), and the protective role of formylated aminonitrile chemistry is supported by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Low-selectivity branched aldehyde diversification to isobutyraldehyde from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals, montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles or flow-through pond margins; poor selectivity; branched products are minor components\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde undergoes aldol diversification and rearrangement within complex aldehyde mixtures, producing trace branched C4 aldehydes including isobutyraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the explicit bottleneck step of the network and is intentionally labeled low-selectivity. The literature identifies isobutyraldehyde formation as the major unresolved problem and points only to poorly selective aldol diversification or complex discharge/radical mixtures as plausible sources. This reaction therefore encodes a minor-yield branch rather than a clean pathway (Preiner et al., 2023; Parker et al., 2011; Keefe et al., 1995).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical Strecker synthesis of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous conditions near pH ~9 where free NH3 is available; evaporitic pool concentration aids equilibration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Isobutyraldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to generate 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the most experimentally validated prebiotic route to valine and is the strongest chemistry in the network. The literature specifically identifies isobutyraldehyde as the requisite aldehyde precursor and confirms the Strecker free-energy landscape and mechanism under mild alkaline aqueous conditions (Miller and Van Trump, 1981; Keefe et al., 1995; Devergne et al., 2021). Mineral agents here are used for concentration and compatibility with the required schema, not because the core Strecker mechanism itself requires them.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis through amide intermediate; irreversible step that drives Strecker sequence forward\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile hydrolyzes stepwise through an amide to the alpha-amino acid, producing racemic valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies nitrile hydrolysis as the irreversible, forward-driving step in the Strecker route and notes aminonitrile half-lives that permit accumulation before conversion, especially in cooler settings (Miller and Van Trump, 1981; Devergne et al., 2021; Miller, 1998). This produces racemic valine, consistent with meteoritic and spark-discharge evidence (Kvenvolden et al., 1970; Johnson et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs-type bridge from isobutyraldehyde to alpha-ketoisovalerate manifold\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"CO2-present aqueous setting; hydantoin-type intermediates implicit; low-confidence compressed bridge\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde, cyanide, ammonia, and carbon dioxide access hydantoin/related intermediates that connect Strecker chemistry with alpha-keto acid/amino acid manifolds, here represented as a net bridge to alpha-ketoisovalerate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is included only because the literature explicitly identifies Bucherer-Bergs chemistry as a bridge between aldehyde-based Strecker chemistry and alpha-keto acid metabolism, but the exact valine-specific sequence is unresolved. It is therefore marked as a compressed, lower-confidence connectivity reaction rather than a high-flux step (Pulletikurti et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Protometabolic generation of alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling or mineral-interface protometabolic network; metabolically congruent but experimentally underdemonstrated for valine precursor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nonenzymatic C-C bond formation in alpha-keto acid chemistry provides a route from pyruvate-centered metabolism toward branched keto acids such as alpha-ketoisovalerate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly allows alpha-ketoisovalerate formation through pyruvate-centered protometabolic condensation as a biologically congruent possibility, while also emphasizing that direct abiotic availability remains undemonstrated. This step is therefore included as a speculative but literature-motivated bridge, not an established reaction (Muchowska et al., 2019; Copley et al., 2005).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/pyrite system or Ni-metal analog\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline to mildly alkaline conditions, pH ~8-9; reductive amination favored over hydroxy acid formation at appropriate Fe(II):Fe(III)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The alpha-keto acid condenses with ammonia to an imine/iminium equivalent that is reduced on iron-sulfur or metal surfaces to the amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is the main metabolically congruent alternative to Strecker synthesis. FeS/H2S-pyrite systems support such reductions, and modern work shows alpha-keto acid to amino acid conversion on iron minerals and Ni under mild alkaline conditions, though alpha-ketoisovalerate-specific prebiotic demonstration remains indirect. The reaction is therefore plausible in principle and strongly motivated by the literature (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber and Wachtershauser, 2003; Barge et al., 2019; Kaur et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-mediated preservation and delayed release of valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"formamide-rich evaporitic microenvironment; protection from reverse Strecker equilibration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reversible N-formylation or solvation in formamide-rich media stabilizes aminonitrile pools against back-reaction, effectively preserving the intermediate for later hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This node is retained as a kinetic preservation process because the literature specifically reports that N-formylation in formamide can protect aminonitriles from reversion of the Strecker equilibrium, thereby improving amino acid yield potential. It is represented as a conservative stabilization loop rather than a new product branch (Green et al., 2021; Green et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Wet-dry condensation of valine to valylvaline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373-393K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"repeated wet-dry cycling in prebiotic pools; concentration by evaporation and salts/clay interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dehydration-driven ester-amide exchange or direct condensation under cycling conditions yields short peptides from concentrated amino acids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This downstream assembly step connects valine production to broader prebiotic relevance. Wet-dry cycling is a strong literature-supported route for peptide formation, although valine oligomerization is less favored than some simpler amino acids. Including this step satisfies the required Surface to Biochemical continuity and concentration logic (Forsythe et al., 2015; Campbell et al., 2019).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical branched-aldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds surface branched aldehyde production, followed by the validated Strecker sequence to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2-to-formate-assisted Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation builds reduced carbon pools before branching to acetaldehyde and then the canonical Strecker endgame.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-linked Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate formation operates in parallel with the branched aldehyde route, sharing downstream HCN and aminonitrile chemistry en route to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-buffered Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface HCN is partitioned partly into formamide-rich settings that stabilize the valine aminonitrile before hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs bridge to keto-acid manifold\",\n      \"description\": \"Aldehyde-based Strecker chemistry is connected to the alpha-ketoisovalerate node through a CO2-enabled Bucherer-Bergs-type bridge, then reduced to valine hydrothermally.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Protometabolic keto-acid route from pyruvate\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate from hydrothermal carbon fixation combines with acetaldehyde in a speculative but literature-motivated protometabolic route to alpha-ketoisovalerate, followed by reductive amination to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-supported keto-acid route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate and acetate generation feed the acetaldehyde/pyruvate network, converging on alpha-ketoisovalerate and then valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed aldehyde-keto acid convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface branched aldehyde chemistry and hydrothermal pyruvate chemistry converge on the keto-acid manifold rather than directly on aminonitrile hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-limited direct Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"This route emphasizes HCN scarcity as a controlling factor: once HCN is photochemically available, the classical Strecker chemistry proceeds to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Target-to-oligopeptide continuation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Valine formed through either Strecker or keto-acid chemistry is concentrated in prebiotic pools and incorporated into short peptides under wet-dry cycling.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "This network is built around the literature-supported conclusion that prebiotic valine formation is best explained by two validated endgame chemistries: (i) Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde, ammonia, and hydrogen cyanide through the valine aminonitrile, and (ii) reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate on iron-sulfur or metallic catalysts. The network therefore makes the branched-precursor bottleneck explicit rather than assuming efficient production of isobutyraldehyde or alpha-ketoisovalerate. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon hubs such as formate, acetate, acetaldehyde, and pyruvate under vent-compatible iron-sulfur catalysis; surface settings supply HCN, aminonitrile formation, branched aldehyde diversification, and concentration under wet-dry and photochemical regimes; biochemical/prebiotic settings provide hydrolysis, transamination connectivity, and peptide assembly. Several pathways are intentionally low-yield or speculative where the literature identifies unresolved gaps, especially in the upstream generation of branched C4 precursors.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "acetic acid", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-4(2)3-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "valine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(6)3-7/h4-5H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C10H20N2O2", "iupac_name": "2-[(2-amino-3-methylbutanoyl)amino]-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valylvaline", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite-catalyzed reduction of carbon dioxide to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite, mackinawite", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface CO2 activation followed by stepwise hydrogenation to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents and release of formate into solution.", "reasoning": "This hydrothermal entry step follows iron-sulfur vent chemistry in which greigite and related FeS phases reduce CO2 under alkaline, H2-rich conditions and is directly aligned with the required hydrothermal reaction set and iron-sulfur world models (Russell et al., 1994; Martin and Russell, 2007). It also reflects the thermodynamic favorability of amino-acid-supporting carbon fixation under hydrothermal conditions (Amend and Shock, 1998)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Iron-sulfur carbon fixation from formate/carbon monoxide to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_015", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite, pyrite", "aqueous": true, "other": "vent micropores, reducing conditions, acetyl-CoA-analog style carbon fixation"}, "mechanism": "Surface-bound C1 units are condensed and reduced on iron-sulfur minerals to an activated acetyl equivalent that hydrolyzes or equilibrates to acetate.", "reasoning": "This reaction represents the vent-compatible acetyl-CoA-analog carbon fixation logic emphasized for early metabolism, where FeS/NiS-like surfaces enable C1 coupling to acetyl species; acetate production is much better supported hydrothermally than direct branched intermediates and therefore serves as a realistic node feeding downstream carbonyl chemistry (Huber and Wachtershauser, 1997; Martin and Russell, 2007; Amend and Shock, 1998)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Magnetite-catalyzed Fischer-Tropsch-type formation of acetaldehyde from carbon monoxide and hydrogen", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "423-573K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite, elemental iron", "aqueous": true, "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal or vent-associated FTT regime; low selectivity mixed carbonyl output"}, "mechanism": "CO hydrogenation on metal/oxide surfaces yields a distribution of reduced carbonyls and alcohols, including low-yield acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal FTT chemistry is supported as a source of hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes rather than amino acids directly. Here acetaldehyde is treated explicitly as a low-selectivity mixed product, not a clean major output, in line with the literature caution on upstream carbonyl supply (McCollom et al., 1999). This avoids overstating formaldehyde-to-acetaldehyde chemistry criticized in previous attempts."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon dioxide on iron minerals", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite, greigite", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline vent/subseafloor setting; low-to-moderate yield alpha-keto acid generation"}, "mechanism": "Sequential mineral-catalyzed reduction and C-C bond formation from CO2-derived C1 units produce alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Direct abiotic pyruvate generation in hydrothermal systems is less firmly established than formate or acetate, so this node is included as a plausible but comparatively weaker vent-derived metabolic hub rather than a dominant flux channel. Its inclusion is justified by the report's recognition of pyruvate-centered protometabolic chemistry and nonenzymatic carbon-fixation analogs (Muchowska et al., 2019; Amend and Shock, 1998)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "UV-driven generation of hydrogen cyanide in surface photochemical settings", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2, sulfide minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "strong UV irradiation, anoxic atmosphere, evaporitic pool or tidal-flat photochemistry; low steady-state HCN concentration"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox surface chemistry generates reduced C-N species and supports HCN accumulation in localized surface reservoirs.", "reasoning": "The literature emphasizes HCN as essential but environmentally limited, with low steady-state concentrations and strong competition among pathways. This surface-photochemical source is therefore represented as a concentration-limited feed rather than an abundant bulk reagent, consistent with atmospheric/photochemical interpretations and cyanosulfidic frameworks (Miyakawa et al., 2002; Patel et al., 2015; Saladino et al., 2006)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface hydration of hydrogen cyanide to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2, phosphate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV-exposed shallow pools; formamide-rich microenvironments possible during evaporation"}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes hydration to formamide, aided by photochemical activation and concentration on mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "Formamide is included because the research specifically highlights formamide/N-formylation chemistry as protective for aminonitriles and relevant to surface prebiotic photochemistry. TiO2-mediated formamide chemistry is well established in prebiotic studies (Saladino et al., 2006), and the protective role of formylated aminonitrile chemistry is supported by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Low-selectivity branched aldehyde diversification to isobutyraldehyde from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals, montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "wet-dry cycles or flow-through pond margins; poor selectivity; branched products are minor components"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde undergoes aldol diversification and rearrangement within complex aldehyde mixtures, producing trace branched C4 aldehydes including isobutyraldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the explicit bottleneck step of the network and is intentionally labeled low-selectivity. The literature identifies isobutyraldehyde formation as the major unresolved problem and points only to poorly selective aldol diversification or complex discharge/radical mixtures as plausible sources. This reaction therefore encodes a minor-yield branch rather than a clean pathway (Preiner et al., 2023; Parker et al., 2011; Keefe et al., 1995)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Classical Strecker synthesis of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, phosphate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "mild aqueous conditions near pH ~9 where free NH3 is available; evaporitic pool concentration aids equilibration"}, "mechanism": "Isobutyraldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to generate 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the most experimentally validated prebiotic route to valine and is the strongest chemistry in the network. The literature specifically identifies isobutyraldehyde as the requisite aldehyde precursor and confirms the Strecker free-energy landscape and mechanism under mild alkaline aqueous conditions (Miller and Van Trump, 1981; Keefe et al., 1995; Devergne et al., 2021). Mineral agents here are used for concentration and compatibility with the required schema, not because the core Strecker mechanism itself requires them."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "aqueous hydrolysis through amide intermediate; irreversible step that drives Strecker sequence forward"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile hydrolyzes stepwise through an amide to the alpha-amino acid, producing racemic valine.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies nitrile hydrolysis as the irreversible, forward-driving step in the Strecker route and notes aminonitrile half-lives that permit accumulation before conversion, especially in cooler settings (Miller and Van Trump, 1981; Devergne et al., 2021; Miller, 1998). This produces racemic valine, consistent with meteoritic and spark-discharge evidence (Kvenvolden et al., 1970; Johnson et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs-type bridge from isobutyraldehyde to alpha-ketoisovalerate manifold", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "CO2-present aqueous setting; hydantoin-type intermediates implicit; low-confidence compressed bridge"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde, cyanide, ammonia, and carbon dioxide access hydantoin/related intermediates that connect Strecker chemistry with alpha-keto acid/amino acid manifolds, here represented as a net bridge to alpha-ketoisovalerate.", "reasoning": "This reaction is included only because the literature explicitly identifies Bucherer-Bergs chemistry as a bridge between aldehyde-based Strecker chemistry and alpha-keto acid metabolism, but the exact valine-specific sequence is unresolved. It is therefore marked as a compressed, lower-confidence connectivity reaction rather than a high-flux step (Pulletikurti et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Protometabolic generation of alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "geothermal cycling or mineral-interface protometabolic network; metabolically congruent but experimentally underdemonstrated for valine precursor"}, "mechanism": "Nonenzymatic C-C bond formation in alpha-keto acid chemistry provides a route from pyruvate-centered metabolism toward branched keto acids such as alpha-ketoisovalerate.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly allows alpha-ketoisovalerate formation through pyruvate-centered protometabolic condensation as a biologically congruent possibility, while also emphasizing that direct abiotic availability remains undemonstrated. This step is therefore included as a speculative but literature-motivated bridge, not an established reaction (Muchowska et al., 2019; Copley et al., 2005)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-363K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS/pyrite system or Ni-metal analog", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline to mildly alkaline conditions, pH ~8-9; reductive amination favored over hydroxy acid formation at appropriate Fe(II):Fe(III)"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-keto acid condenses with ammonia to an imine/iminium equivalent that is reduced on iron-sulfur or metal surfaces to the amino acid.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is the main metabolically congruent alternative to Strecker synthesis. FeS/H2S-pyrite systems support such reductions, and modern work shows alpha-keto acid to amino acid conversion on iron minerals and Ni under mild alkaline conditions, though alpha-ketoisovalerate-specific prebiotic demonstration remains indirect. The reaction is therefore plausible in principle and strongly motivated by the literature (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber and Wachtershauser, 2003; Barge et al., 2019; Kaur et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Formamide-mediated preservation and delayed release of valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "formamide-rich evaporitic microenvironment; protection from reverse Strecker equilibration"}, "mechanism": "Reversible N-formylation or solvation in formamide-rich media stabilizes aminonitrile pools against back-reaction, effectively preserving the intermediate for later hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "This node is retained as a kinetic preservation process because the literature specifically reports that N-formylation in formamide can protect aminonitriles from reversion of the Strecker equilibrium, thereby improving amino acid yield potential. It is represented as a conservative stabilization loop rather than a new product branch (Green et al., 2021; Green et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Wet-dry condensation of valine to valylvaline", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "373-393K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": false, "other": "repeated wet-dry cycling in prebiotic pools; concentration by evaporation and salts/clay interfaces"}, "mechanism": "Dehydration-driven ester-amide exchange or direct condensation under cycling conditions yields short peptides from concentrated amino acids.", "reasoning": "This downstream assembly step connects valine production to broader prebiotic relevance. Wet-dry cycling is a strong literature-supported route for peptide formation, although valine oligomerization is less favored than some simpler amino acids. Including this step satisfies the required Surface to Biochemical continuity and concentration logic (Forsythe et al., 2015; Campbell et al., 2019)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical branched-aldehyde Strecker route", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds surface branched aldehyde production, followed by the validated Strecker sequence to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "CO2-to-formate-assisted Strecker route", "description": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation builds reduced carbon pools before branching to acetaldehyde and then the canonical Strecker endgame.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Pyruvate-linked Strecker route", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate formation operates in parallel with the branched aldehyde route, sharing downstream HCN and aminonitrile chemistry en route to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formamide-buffered Strecker route", "description": "Surface HCN is partitioned partly into formamide-rich settings that stabilize the valine aminonitrile before hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_013", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_013", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs bridge to keto-acid manifold", "description": "Aldehyde-based Strecker chemistry is connected to the alpha-ketoisovalerate node through a CO2-enabled Bucherer-Bergs-type bridge, then reduced to valine hydrothermally.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_005", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Protometabolic keto-acid route from pyruvate", "description": "Pyruvate from hydrothermal carbon fixation combines with acetaldehyde in a speculative but literature-motivated protometabolic route to alpha-ketoisovalerate, followed by reductive amination to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_007", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Formate-supported keto-acid route", "description": "Hydrothermal formate and acetate generation feed the acetaldehyde/pyruvate network, converging on alpha-ketoisovalerate and then valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Mixed aldehyde-keto acid convergence route", "description": "Surface branched aldehyde chemistry and